<DOCNO> XIE19970227.0003 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CPPCC Hong Kong Members Arrive in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 26 (Xinhua) -- Members of the National
Committee of the Chinese People's Political Consultative
Conference (CPPCC) from Hong Kong arrived in Beijing today to
attend the Fifth Session of the Eighth CPPCC National Committee,
which is scheduled to open Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Wang Julu, deputy secretary-general of the CPPCC National
Committee, met the 61-member Hong Kong delegation at the airport.
</P>
<P>
All the members expressed full confidence in the smooth
transition of Hong Kong. Member Maria Tam Wai-chu said that the
Hong Kong people grieved over the passing of Mr. Deng Xiaoping,
and would turn grief into strength and carry forward Deng's behest
by firmly implementing the principle of "one country, two systems"
and contributing to Hong Kong's long-term prosperity and
stability.
</P>
<P>
"It is my firm belief that the central government will be able
to carry out the principle of 'one country, two systems' and the
policy of reform and opening up in a thorough way," she added.
</P>
<P>
Member Wan Tai Min said that Hong Kong now enjoys social
stability and economic prosperity, and will certainly return to
the embrace of the motherland smoothly on July 1 this year, adding
that Hong Kong's economic growth to a large extent hinges on the a
highly-competent and efficient team of civil servants.
</P>
<P>
"Recently the central government announced the appointment of
leading officials in the first government of the Hong Kong special
administrative region (HKSAR), and all principal Chinese civil
servants currently in office were on the list of appointees," he
noted.
</P>
<P>
"This has greatly boosted the morale of the civil servants in
Hong Kong, enhanced the Hong Kong people's confidence, and showed
the Chinese government's determination to implement the principles
of 'one country, two systems' and 'Hong Kong people governing Hong
Kong'," he noted, saying that this would help the smooth
transition of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong members also showed a seething enthusiasm for
involving themselves in the country's government and political
affairs.
</P>
<P>
Describing the motherland's reunification as an aspiration
shared by the Chinese all over the world, Member Yew Mui Leong
suggested that the relevant sides give scope to the Chines culture
and the work concerning overseas Chinese. And he proposed sorting
out a theme that can be accepted by the Chinese people on both
sides of the Taiwan Straits and across the world, for the sake of
promoting the reunification of the motherland.
</P>
<P>
"I am trying to do so with my painting exhibits," said Yew, who
hosted a series of exhibits of paintings featuring the relations
between Dr. Sun Yat-sen, forerunner of China's democratic
revolution, and the overseas Chinese.
</P>
<P>
Maria Tam Wai-chu said Hong Kong and the interior area have
different legal systems, and that she hoped to contribute her
share for the legal cooperation and coordination between Hong
Kong and the interior area.
</P>
<P>
"As a CPPCC member, it is my duty bound to help more Hong Kong
residents to acquire a better understanding of the laws in the
interior area and encourage them to invest in the interior area,
and to help the interior areas to use Hong Kong as a bridge to
draw more investment from overseas," she said.
</P>
<P>
There are a total of 108 CPPCC National Committee members in
the Hong Kong region. Some of them are already in Beijing,
attending sessions of the Standing Committee of the CPPCC National
Committee and of the Preparatory Committee of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region.
</P>
<P>
Sixteen members of the CPPCC National Committee from the region
of Macao, headed by NG Fok, a member of the Standing Committee of
the CPPCC National Committee, also arrived here this afternoon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
