<HEADLINE> Olympic Champion Windsurfer Named HK's Sports Star of Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, February 26 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's Olympic champion
woman windsurfer Lee Lai Shan made history here Wednesday evening
as she was named for a record fifth consecutive time as Hong
Kong's sports star of the year.
</P>
<P>
The veteran athlete, known here as Shan Shan, top-ranked the
list of six "Coca-Cola Hong Kong Sports Stars" for 1996.
</P>
<P>
Also honored was wheelchair fencer Cheung Wei Leung, who won
four gold medals at last year's Paralympics in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
Others named were cyclist Wong Kam Po (for the second time),
table tennis players Chai Po Wa (ninth time) and Chan Tan Lui
(seventh time) and Wushu master Ng Siu Ching (third time).
</P>
<P>
"I'm very happy since this is the fifth time for me to receive
the 'best of the best' award," said Lee after the awarding
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
"It's pretty hard to take both college studies and training and
 I'll try my best," she said, referring to her studies in the
Camberra University of Australia.
</P>
<P>
"I will spend more time in study for the first half of this
year. But that does not mean I will not train. Instead I will
train.
</P>
<P>
"And I will train very, very hard in the second half of the
year, for the Asian Games (in Bangkok next year) and for the world
championships in December this year in Perth, western Australia,"
she said.
</P>
<P>
"The weather there is very windy," she said. Lee has never
been to the Western part of Australia.
</P>
<P>
The year's junior sports stars named tonight were Lee Yin Yee
(athletics), Fong Lik Sun (swimming), Chiu Wing Yin (squash), Liu
Kwok Wa (badminton), Cheng Hing Lun (windsurfing) and Cheng Ka Ho
(Wushu).
</P>
<P>
Named as the sports team of the year was Hong Kong's cerebral
palsy 4x100 meters relay team, which won the race in a new world
record time at the Atlanta Games last year for the disabled.
</P>
</TEXT>
