<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Enliven Housing Sales by Financial Restructuring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 26 (Xinhua) -- China is taking steps to boost
housing commercialization by setting up housing-related banks,
public funding and home-owner loans and mortgages.
</P>
<P>
According to a senior official with the Ministry of
Construction, China continues to suffer from slack housing
sales. The year-end figure of 1996 showed that a total of 50
million sq m of residences were lying idle nationwide, including
30 million sq m of ordinary houses.
</P>
<P>
The residents' poor purchasing power and the higher housing
prices account for the excess of residences, the official said.
</P>
<P>
To promote housing commercialization and reform, the Ministry
of Finance has already reduced or remitted 48 varieties of
irrational taxes concerning housing construction and sales, in a
bid to secure a rational commercial housing price.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the country is setting up housing-related banks on a
trial basis in a number of cities, which are expected to provide a
financial guarantee as well as loans and mortgages for residents'
housing purchase.
</P>
<P>
And great headway is being made in raising housing funding,
which has topped nearly 100 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
China is continuing to draft a series of rules governing
administration, operation and appreciation of the housing
fund. 
</P>
</TEXT>
