<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Central Bank on Inflationary Price </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, February 26 (Xinhua) -- The Reserve Bank of Zimbabwe
today expressed concern about the spate of price increases, which
it said could trigger another inflationary spiral.
</P>
<P>
The central bank said in its latest economic bulletin that
efforts to reduce inflation, which was pegged at 15.8 percent in
January, could be "frustrated" by periodic adjustments to
administered prices.
</P>
<P>
It said the 4-9 percent fuel price rise announced at the
beginning of the year was still to be felt, so was the impact of
the increase in rural bus fares, which went up by 15.5 percent
last week.
</P>
<P>
The bank said despite the price rises, it would continue to
closely monitor inflationary trends with a view to keeping
inflation low.
</P>
<P>
"As in the past, however, efforts in this direction have been
frustrated by various factors, notably periodic adjustments to
administered prices," said the bank.
</P>
<P>
It, however, said inflation was unlikely to exceed 20 percent by
June this year, slightly above the original forecast of 17 percent
made last September. enditem

