<HEADLINE> Industrialization Urged for Flower Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 26 (Xinhua) -- Chinese floriculturists have
been encouraged to develop flower-growing into a profitable
industry through increasing production, improving product quality
and tapping rich floral resources.
</P>
<P>
The plans for developing flower production should be designed
to be suitable for the development of the whole agricultural
sector, Chen Muhua, vice-chairperson of the Standing Committee of
the National People's Congress, said here today.
</P>
<P>
The government should issue a series of preferential policies
to support the sector. Some measures should be taken to improve
the quality of flowers, such as improving strains, updating
cultivation technology and training qualified workers, Chen told a
national conference on industrialization of flower production.
</P>
<P>
"We should tap our abundant floral resources as far as possible
and turn them into commodities by making full use of the cheap
labor in the vast rural areas," Chen said.
</P>
<P>
She also pointed out that the sector will enjoy a huge
potential domestic market, since Chinese people still pay little
attention to flowers, compared with other kinds of consumption
goods.
</P>
<P>
China's flower market has been dominated by cut flowers, potted
and decorative plants, lawns and traditional potted landscapes,
according to Deputy Minister of agriculture Liu Chengguo.
</P>
<P>
China will produce two billion sprays of cut flowers annually
by the year 2000, involving seven billion yuan in output value and
earning 200 million US dollars through exports, Liu said.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
