<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Notable Progress in Three Gorges Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 26 (Xinhua) -- China has made "notable
progress" in building the Three Gorges Project since the world's
largest water-control scheme started four years ago, a project
official said here today.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1996 construction workers had excavated 126
million cu m of earth and rocks, approximately 85 percent of the
total to be excavated, said Lu Youmei, president of the China
Yangtze River Three Gorges Project Development Corporation.
</P>
<P>
Workers have also filled more than 48 million cu m of earth and
rocks, or 52 percent of the total backfill, Lu said at a ceremony
held for the issuance of one billion yuan-worth of bonds to
increase funding for the project.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the water-diversion channel, which is to
redirect the flow of the Yangtze after the river is dammed this
November, is near completion. The channel is expected to hold
water in May and be navigable in October, Lu said.
</P>
<P>
The expressway linking the dam site with the nearby towns, the
Xiling Yangtze Bridge, the Yangjiawan Wharf and the Three Gorges
Airport has been put into service, and various infrastructure
facilities now meet the demands of major sub-projects, he added.
</P>
<P>
"Construction of the project is slightly ahead of schedule,
investment remains within the state budget, construction quality
is in accordance with design and resettlement has made a good
start," the corporation president said.
</P>
<P>
"The damming of the Yangtze this November, the first-stage goal
of the project, is now a certainty," he said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of resettlement, Guo Shuyan, deputy director of the
Three Gorges Project Construction Commission under the State
Council, said that China has developed 6,600 ha of land in the
reservoir area and on it built houses covering a floor space of
578,000 sq m for farmers and 498,000 sq m of housing for urban
residents.
</P>
<P>
Guo went on to say that the country has completed the
reconstruction of 99 factories and is moving another 256.
</P>
<P>
He said 70 percent of the infrastructure facilities that will
be submerged after the damming of the Yangtze have been rebuilt
elsewhere, and 42,300 people have relocated.
</P>
<P>
"Funding for the Three Gorges Project has been sufficient so
far," the official said. By the end of 1996 China had invested
20.8 billion yuan in the project, guaranteeing the progress of the
project's construction and resettlement work. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
