<DOCNO> XIE19970227.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greenspan Warns of Overheated Runup in Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 26 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Federal Reserve (Fed)
Chairman Alan Greenspan said today that "caution seems especially
warranted" over the extraordinary runup in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
During a testimony in the U.S. Congress, Greenspan said, "There
are reasons in the current environment to keep this question on
the table."
</P>
<P>
"History demonstrates that participants in financial markets
are susceptible to waves of optimism," he said. "Excessive
optimism sows the seeds of its own reversal in the form of
imbalances that tend to grow over time."
</P>
<P>
Greenspan roiled stock markets over the world in early December
with his now-famous question about whether "irrational exuberance"
was driving the market. His remark today also resulted in a sharp
plunge in the Dow Jones average of industrial stocks in the
morning.
</P>
<P>
Greenspan balanced his warning by noting that members of the
U.S. Fed must look for trouble and "even I must admit our economic
prospects are quite favorable."
</P>
<P>
Greenspan listed the factors he believes have kept inflation
unusually contained: job insecurity restraining wage growth,
intense global competition, a strong dollar keeping a lid on
import prices and wide profit margins that give firms room to
accommodate increased costs without raising retail prices.
</P>
<P>
But he said that all of those factors may be temporary and he
could not rule out a preemptive increase in interest rates to
hold economic growth and prices in check because the stock price
runup could help feed inflation.
</P>
<P>
He cautioned that given the long lags between interest rate
changes and their impact on the economy as a whole, "we cannot
rule out a situation in which a preemptive policy tightening may
become appropriate before any sign of actual higher inflation
becomes evident."
</P>
<P>
Today's testimony accompanied the Fed's twice-a-year report to
the U.S. Congress on its handling of monetary policy and economic
expectations.
</P>
<P>
In its forecast for 1997, the Fed predicted economic growth of
between 2 percent and 2.25 percent, inflation between 2.75 percent
and 3 percent and an unemployment rate between 5.25 percent and
5.5 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
