<DOCNO> XIE19970227.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France, US Resume Talks on NATO Europeanization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, February 26 (Xinhua) -- France and the United States
have resumed over the past few weeks negotiations on the
Europeanization of the Naples-based Southern Command of the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO), reported the local daily Le
Monde today.
</P>
<P>
The report, quoting official sources, said that although little
progress has been made in reaching an agreement over the issue,
the United States has for the first time shown its willingness to
look for a compromise acceptable to both.
</P>
<P>
France has insisted that the Southern Command be headed by a
European officer and that a U.S. admiral remain the commander of
the Sixth Fleet of the United States Navy and some air and navy
forces of European allies.
</P>
<P>
Or, as France suggested, the United States will be in charge of
"functional" operations of NATO forces in the region, while
Europe commands the "territorial" operations of the allied
forces.
</P>
<P>
Washington rejected the demand and presented a counter-proposal
which includes the creation of a NATO rapid action force in the
Mediterranean region to be headed by a European officer, according
to the report.
</P>
<P>
The United States also suggested a sharing of responsibilities
for the different territories of the region between the United
States and Europe.
</P>
<P>
The United States wants to keep its control over allied forces
in the eastern part of the Mediterranean and the Middle East,
while the western part of the Mediterranean could be put under the
control of Europeans, said the report.
</P>
<P>
France called the U.S. proposal insufficient although it agreed
to study "different possible packages" of proposals from
Washington.
</P>
<P>
France bases its demand for the take-over of the Southern
Command on the theory that Europe and the United States do not
necessarily share the same interests in the Mediterranean region,
which has become the most sensitive area for the security of
Europe after the fall of the Berlin Wall.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the idea of a double NATO command for the region is
not new. From 1952 to 1967, an American admiral commanded the
Southern Command from Naples, while a British admiral commanded a
NATO Mediterranean force from Malta, which was baptized Afmed.
</P>
<P>
France has made it clear that if negotiations with U.S. do not
produce any positive result before the NATO Madrid summit in July,
it will stay out of its integrated military command structure as
it has since 1966. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970227.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Not to Accept Preconditions for EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, February 26 (Xinhua) -- The Cyprus government will
not accept a solution to the Cyprus problem as precondition for
its accession to the European Union (EU), a government spokesman
said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at his daily press briefing, spokesman Yiannakis
Cassoulides said that "Of course, any effort to set the solution
of the Cyprus problem as a precondition for entry to the EU
worries us."
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus government "will strive not to allow the two issues
to be connected and to prove that it is not the side to be blamed
if a solution is not reached when accession talks begin," the
spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
Cassoulides pointed out the EU did not support simultaneous
accession talks with the Turkish Cypriots, but some of its member
states made the proposal asking for Turkish Cypriot participation.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Britain, France and Germany insisted on the
participation of all Cypriots in the accession process. Greece
had made counterproposals on the issue, which were turned down.
</P>
<P>
As a result, a meeting between the EU and Cyprus, within the
framework of the Cyprus-EU structured dialogue, was postponed in
Brussels in view of disagreement among EU member states over
Turkish Cypriot participation.
</P>
<P>
Cassoulides noted the Cyprus government will only be
satisfied when the EU issues a common communique regarding
Cyprus' political dialogue.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said he agrees with the Greek position and
noted the EU must reaffirm its decision of March 6, 1995, whereby
accession talks will begin with Cyprus six months after the end
of the Intergovernmental Conference.
</P>
<P>
Cassoulides reiterated that the Cyprus government does not
disagree with EU efforts to inform Turkish Cypriots of the
benefits they will have from the island's EU accession.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus, which has been remained divided since 1974, applied for
full EU membership in 1990. 
