<HEADLINE> Hezbollah Warns of Possible Attack on Northern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, February 26 (Xinhua) -- A top official of the Lebanese
Hezbollah warned here today that his organization could resume
Katyusha attacks on northern Israel if the Jewish state continues
"aggressions" against Lebanese civilians.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Naim Kassem, Hezbollah's Deputy Secretary General, was
quoted by the Free Lebanon Radio as saying that a Lebanese-Israeli
truce agreement, which was reached last April, does not rule out
the possibility that Israeli civilians are targeted by Katyusha
rockets if Israel continues violating the agreement.
</P>
<P>
The shiite pro-Iranian Hezbollah, or Party of God, spearheads
a guerrilla warfare to oust Israeli occupation forces from a
1,100-square-kilometer enclave in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
"We are waiting and weighing whether things have reached the
limit requiring a real response which constitutes a real
retaliation for the aggression," Kassem said.
</P>
<P>
Seven Lebanese civilians have been killed in bombardments of
the Israeli forces and the Israeli-backed South Lebanon Army
militia since the implementation of the cease-fire
understanding, which ended a 17-day Israeli blitz in south
Lebanon in April 1996.
</P>
<P>
Under the understanding, which demands civilians on both
sides of the border be kept away from military operations, a
five-nation monitoring committee comprising France, Israel,
Lebanon, Syria and the United States was set up to supervise
violations of the cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
The committee has met for 14 times to discuss complaints
lodged by Lebanon and Israel against each other over breaches of
the cease-fire understanding.
</P>
<P>
However, the only thing the committee has done was to issue
repeated non-mandatory statements, drawing attacks for
incapability to avert civilian casualties in Lebanon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
