<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK SFA Bans Seventh EX-Barings Director </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 26 (Xinhua) -- Britain's Securities and
Futures Authority (SFA), the financial market regulator, banned
James Bax Tuesday from acting as director of any securities
business for 21 months for his role in the collapse of the bank in
1995.
</P>
<P>
Bax, 44, head of Barings Securities in Asia and former boss of
rogue trader Nick Leeson, became the seventh former director of
the merchant bank to be suspended by the SFA.
</P>
<P>
The SFA said Bax had admitted that he failed to take action to
remedy control weakness in the Barings Singapore organization and
did not act quickly or firmly enough to investigate Leeson.
</P>
<P>
However, Bax said that he had to accept the ruling that he
should be banned for 21 months, running from the start of the
SFA's proceedings against him in March 1996 until the end of 1997,
and pay 10,000 pound (16,300 US dollar) costs because he could not
afford the substantial costs of defending himself against the
SFA's charges.
</P>
<P>
The SFA has already finished action against seven of the nine
former Barings chiefs it found had failed to show "due skill, care
and diligence" in overseeing Leeson.
</P>
<P>
Ian Hopkins, former head of treasury at Barings, has a week to
decide whether to appeal against an order banning him for three
years while Ron Baker is the only ex-Barings director to appeal
against an SFA reprimand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
