</P>
<P>
"The neighborhood at Har Homa will include approximately 6,500
housing units. The first stage will include approximately 2,500
units," said the communique.
</P>
<P>
The committee also decided to allow Palestinians to build
3,015 housing units in 10 neighborhoods in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The decision came after Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu gave
green light to the plan earlier this week in spite of
furious opposition from the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu issued a warning to the Palestinians saying that it
would be a grave mistake if they respond to the plans with
violence.
</P>
<P>
Israeli security sources threatened that any Palestinian
violence could delay the first phase of further Israeli
redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
In an apparent attempt to alleviate anger of the Egyptian
people, who are valiant supporters of the Palestinian cause,
Netanyahu phoned President Hosni Mubarak this morning to inform
him he was going ahead with the building plan.
</P>
<P>
In his first reaction to the anticipated decision, Jordan's
Crown Prince Hassan Tuesday informed Israel that he canceled his
visit to Israel at the weekend.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the committee meeting, peace activists from the
left-wing Meretz Party and Peace Now organization demonstrated
outside the Prime Minister's Office demanding that the committee
put on hold the project.
</P>
<P>
Security was reinforced In Jerusalem and in parts of the West
Bank today for possible violent resistance by the Palestinians
over the issue of Har Homa.
</P>
<P>
The shooting incident in Hizmeh village Tuesday evening further
complicated the security matters in the city.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli authorities are concerned that thousands of
Palestinians might resort to violence after prayers on Temple
Mount in Jerusalem's Old City Friday. 
</P>
