<HEADLINE> Egypt, Niger Voice Concern About Great Lakes Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, February 26 (Xinhua) -- Egypt and Niger today expressed
their concern about the volatile situation in the countries known
as the Great Lakes region of Africa and called for peaceful
settlement of the mounting hostilities.
</P>
<P>
In a joint statement, Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and
Niger President Barre Mainassara appealed to the parties concerned
to reach a peaceful solution to the regional problems.
</P>
<P>
They called for more international support for maintaining
peace in the region and stressed the importance of respecting
international borders and national integrity of all countries in
the region.
</P>
<P>
The Great Lakes region includes Burundi, Rwanda, Zaire, Uganda
and Tanzania. Zaire has accused Rwanda and Uganda of sponsoring
rebels in the country. The three countries are all inflicted with
civil wars with ethnic Hutus against Tutsis.
</P>
<P>
The statement, released at the end of Mainassara's three-day
visit, also reiterated the importance of Afro-Arab cooperation and
called for close cooperation between the Organization of African
Unity and the Organization of Islamic Conference.
</P>
<P>
The Niger president arrived here Monday for his first ever
visit to Egypt since he assumed office in 1996. He is accompanied
by a high-level delegation grouping ministers of trade,
agriculture, interior and foreign affairs. 
</P>
