<HEADLINE> "Flawed Advice" About Gulf War Syndrome: Defense </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 26 (Xinhua) -- There were "serious flaws" in
advice given to ministers about the use of harmful pesticides by
British forces in the Gulf War, said the British Ministry of
Defense.
</P>
<P>
A critical report by Sir Richard Mottram, the ministry's
permanent under-secretary released today, found wide-ranging
"internal confusion" in the Defense Ministry about the use of
harmful pesticides during the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
Ministers were made about the extent to which pesticides had
been deployed in the Gulf, and civil servants had failed to pass
on their knowledge in the appropriate way.
</P>
<P>
Armed Forces Minister Nicholas Soames was quizzed by MPs over
claims he misled the Commons on the issue.
</P>
<P>
He had told MPs that the pesticides were hardly used in the
war, but later had to admit their use had been widespread.
</P>
<P>
"Information was neither assessed nor followed up properly,"
the report said.
</P>
<P>
The internal inquiry could lead to disciplinary proceeding
against individual civil servants and officers.
</P>
<P>
Soames commissioned the inquiry in December after he was
forced to apologize to the House of Commons for misleading
parliament over the use of the pesticides.
</P>
<P>
Campaigners claim that these chemicals could be responsible for
Gulf War Syndrome.
</P>
<P>
David Clark, shadow defense spokesman, wrote to Soames Monday,
demanding that he announce the findings of the syndrome.
</P>
<P>
"If Nicholas Soames takes seriously his responsibilities, he
will come to the House of Commons to make a fully public and
accountable statement," he said.
</P>
<P>
Former Defense Minister Sir Archie Hamilton said ministers
could not be expected to know everything and Labor's claim was
election "hysteria." 
</P>
</TEXT>
