<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France, European Parliament Clash Over Immigration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, February 26 (Xinhua) -- The French government and the
European Parliament today raised voices in their clash over the
new immigration law of France, which the European Parliament said
should be withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
The president of the European Parliament, Spanish conservative
deputy Jose Maria Gil-Robles who is on a visit here, today
canceled a meeting with French Foreign Minister Herve de Charette,
after the latter described the European Parliament as "not worth
its name."
</P>
<P>
"France considers it shocking that the European Parliament
could debate the questions which concern the sovereignty of its
member states and the responsibility of their governments and
national parliaments," said de Charette.
</P>
<P>
He said that he would raise the issue at the next European
Union (EU) foreign ministers' session and during meetings of the
Inter-Governmental Council of the EU.
</P>
<P>
European deputies of the Strasbourg-based European Parliament
adopted last Thursday a resolution which said the new immigration
law of France reminded one of "appeals for denouncement" of
foreigners of the old times.
</P>
<P>
The text, adopted with 213 votes for and 118 against, was
presented by several Euro-deputies from the leftist and ecologist
parties of France itself.
</P>
<P>
The immigration law, also called the Debre bill in reference to
its author, French Interior Minister Jean-Louis Debre, is strongly
contested at home as it requires French homes to apply for
certificates to accommodate foreigners and inform police their
time of departure from France.
</P>
<P>
France opposes strengthening of the power of the European
Parliament in the process of renovation of the EU mechanism, while
Germany and several other European countries want to see a bigger
role to be played by the European Parliament, the only
democratically elected establishment of the EU.
</P>
<P>
France could seize this opportunity to reaffirm the priority of
national parliaments of European countries over the European
Parliament.
</P>
<P>
So far, the power of the European Parliament is limited to
approve the EU annual budget and control the activities of the
European Commission, the executive organ of the EU. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
