<HEADLINE> TUC Pledges to Limit Strikes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 26 (Xinhua) -- Britain's Trade Union Congress
(TUC) today pledged itself to minimizing industrial disputes as a
plan to reduce its potential to embarrass the future government
due to be elected in May.
</P>
<P>
A document entitled "Partners for Progress" called for
employers and unions to work together to solve problems in the
field of employment, particularly in training.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot afford to be adversarial in industrial relations,"
John Monks, TUC general secretary, said in an interview with
reporters.
</P>
<P>
"We will try to avoid strikes and seek far greater involvement
of third parties in conciliation and arbitration," he added.
</P>
<P>
Monks wanted to create "an active agenda with employers" to
improve corporate performance through improved training and
increased investment.
</P>
<P>
"Inherent in the social partnership model outlined in this
report is the need to minimize industrial disputes," the document
said.
</P>
<P>
Political observers here believe that the aim of the document
is to ensure that unions could not be blamed for any future
collapse of a Labor government.
</P>
<P>
"The background is that two out of the last three periods of
Labor in office ended after disputes with unions," Monks said.
</P>
<P>
Persistent strikes during the 1970s made the unions very
unpopular. 
</P>
</TEXT>
