<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Makes Breakthrough in Treating Liver Cancer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, February 27 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese University of
Hong Kong has achieved a breakthrough in early diagnosis and
treatment of liver cancer, a spokesman of the university said here
today.
</P>
<P>
At a press briefing, Philip Johnson, chairman of the Department
of Clinical Oncology, said researchers in the university have
discovered a new method called isoelectric to determine the nature
of serum alpha-fetoprotein (AFP) in different kinds of diseases.
</P>
<P>
According to Johnson, the higher the AFP level, the more likely
the patient has the cancer.
</P>
<P>
He said the method helps diagnose liver cancer at the early
stage and in turn increase the chances of curing the disease.
</P>
<P>
The researchers of the university found that AFPs from
different clinical conditions give different bands in the gels
under the electric field.
</P>
<P>
He said that by examining the bands instead of using
radiological methods which can not detect tumors less than one
centimeter in size, doctors can accurately diagnose the clinical
condition.
</P>
<P>
Primary liver cancer is the number-two killer among all cancers
in Hong Kong. Figures from the Hong Kong Cancer Registry show that
more than 1,500 new cases are found each year and last year 1,200
patients died of liver cancer in the territory.
</P>
<P>
Joseph W. Y. Lau, chairman of the Department of Surgery of the
university, said they have also made a breakthrough in the
treatment of liver cancer through selective internal radiation
therapy.
</P>
<P>
Researchers have found that the use of 43 technetium labeled
macroaggregated albumin and gamma scan can accurately simulate the
actual treatment of selective internal radiation, which has made
the treatment safer and more effective in treating liver cancer.
</P>
<P>
Lau said the treatment method is effective for liver cancer
patients in severe condition.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970227.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibetan Deputy To NPC On Deng Xiaoping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 27 (Xinhua) -- When he was three, he was
selected as the reincarnated soul boy of a living Buddha of
Tibetan Buddhism, but he grew up as an expert of Tibetan study and
managed to become a professor in a leading British university.
</P>
<P>
Tudeng Nyima, a deputy of Tibetan nationality to the Eighth
National People's Congress (NPC), returned to Beijing from London
to attend the top legislature's fifth session due to open on March
1.
</P>
<P>
"I went to study in England at my own expense in 1991, and now
teach at the School of Oriental and African Studies of the
University of London," said Nyima, 54.
</P>
<P>
He is also director of the Tibetology Center in Sichuan
Province, southwest China, and vice-president of the Sichuan
Provincial School of Tibetan Language.
</P>
<P>
In an interview, Nyima said that he heard of Deng Xiaoping's
passing away on radio the day before he left London.
</P>
<P>
"I have been very sad since then," he said. "Comrade Deng
Xiaoping always showed great concern for ethnic and religious
affairs, and played a key role in the publication of the 'Grand
Tibetan-Chinese Dictionary' in the early 1980s, a great event for
Tibetan culture."
</P>
<P>
He recalled how Deng responded promptly to a letter from Zhaxi
Cering, a member of the National Committee of the Chinese People's
Political Consultative Conference, and personally experienced the
compilation and publication of the dictionary.
</P>
<P>
"I am now collaborating with some international Tibetologists
to translate it into a Tibetan-English dictionary, which to date
has entered the phase of final editing," he added.
</P>
<P>
Also thanks to Deng's efforts to restore the status of
intellectuals and develop ethnic culture and education after the
Cultural Revolution, he said, the Sichuan Provincial School of
Tibetan Language was founded in 1981, which helped foster a large
number of successors to Tibetan culture.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that each time he returns home, he is
impressed by drastic improvements in people's life and cultural
prosperity among various ethnic minorities.
</P>
<P>
"In recent years, we have published so many books and magazines
in Tibetan language that even some people abroad with a hostile
attitude toward China have to admit that Tibetan culture is being
carried on and further developed," he noted.
</P>
<P>
He said that he would put forth two proposals during the coming
NPC session. One concerns the need to send books and magazines
about China's ethnic minorities, especially about Tibetan culture,
abroad for sale, to help foreign scholars acquire a better
understanding of the development of Tibetology in China.
</P>
<P>
"I will also ask the government to arrange short-term lectures
abroad for scholars of different ages of the Tibetan ethnic group,
to help foreigners know the real Tibet, and widen the horizons of
young scholars," he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
