<HEADLINE> European SMEs Need More Financial Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Small and medium-sized
enterprises (SMEs) in Europe need more support from bankers to
compete with companies around the world, said a EU report
published today.
</P>
<P>
Four out of every five SMEs rely on bank overdrafts and loans
as their primary source of funding, and most of the firms remain
under-capitalized all the time, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The report, published after one year's study by a team on how
to improve SME financing, examined bankers' best practices, such
as risk assessments, treatment of high-risk clients and incentives
for successful SMEs.
</P>
<P>
EU Commissioner Christos Papoutsis, responsible for enterprise
policy, said in his foreword to the report, "it not only
constitutes a valuable exchange of experience and opinion, but
that it succeeds in moving forward the whole dialogue between
banks and SMEs, providing a firm foundation for future work."
</P>
<P>
He added that only a genuine and long-term commitment on both
sides can help small companies to build a sound footing for their
financial affairs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
