<HEADLINE> Safari Rally Teams to Modify Cars for High Temperatures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Three major teams in the
Safari Rally are racing against time to modify their cars for the
punishing bumps and heat of dry season in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The three-day rally scheduled to start on March 1 is held three
weeks earlier this year to avoid the rainy season beginning from
March.
</P>
<P>
However, the current dry season leave the route very dusty and
the weather is so hot that the in-car temperature could rise up to
60 degrees Centigrade.
</P>
<P>
The Subaru team, which recorded 23 points in the first two
rounds of the new 14-round series, are fitting additional air
ducting under the bonnet and looking at a second air/oil engine
cooler.
</P>
<P>
The Ford team, standing at 16 points, will be using a seven
gear-box and revised differential calibrations to increase their
speed range.
</P>
<P>
Their cooling efforts even extend to the cockpit, where the
driver will wear special cool suits to help cope with the heat in
the car.
</P>
<P>
The team Mitsubishi has also improved engine cooling system and
developed special shock absorber settings for the Safari Rally,
the third round of the 1997 World Rally Championships. 
</P>
</TEXT>
