<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vice-Premier on Voluntary Tree Planting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Voluntary tree planting, which
was initiated by the late leader Deng Xiaoping, will continue to
be carried out throughout China, a senior Chinese official has
told a national conference on afforestation.
</P>
<P>
"We will carry out the behest of Comrade Deng Xiaoping and push
forward the voluntary tree planting drive around the country,"
Vice-Premier Jiang Chunyun told the 16th Plenary Meeting of the
National Afforestation Committee (NAC), which opened here today.
</P>
<P>
Deng, who died at the age 93 on February 19, launched the drive
16 years ago. He earnestly practised what he advocated while he
was able.
</P>
<P>
Jiang, also director of the NAC, said the voluntary drive has
made remarkable contributions to greening the country in the past
16 years.
</P>
<P>
China's forest coverage rate has risen to 13.9 percent from
12.7 percent in the 1980s, and almost all the barren hills and
mountains in 12 provinces and autonomous regions have been made
green.
</P>
<P>
The urban green-coverage rate increased to 23.8 percent from
19.2 percent in the same period, and the per capita public green
area has reached 5.7 sq m.
</P>
<P>
However, the task of afforestation in China is still an arduous
and protracted one, since the country has more than 2.6 million sq
km of desertificated land, which is expanding at a rate of 2,400
sq km each year, Jiang stressed.
</P>
<P>
Reckless lumbering in some areas of central and western China
also makes afforestation very difficult, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Desertification control in the central and western parts of
the country is very important for local economic development and
improvement of the whole country's ecological environment," Jiang
said.
</P>
<P>
"Various kinds of measures should be taken and the whole of
society should be mobilized to participate in the voluntary tree
planting drive," he stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
