<HEADLINE> Indonesia, Croatia to Strengthen Economic Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia and Croatia agreed
today to apply counter-trade schemes to forge trade and economic
ties between the two countries, a senior Indonesian official said
here today.
</P>
<P>
"Croatia is interested to import Indonesian coal, while
Indonesia wants to purchase fishing boats from the Balkan state,"
State Minister/Secretary Moerdiono said after President Soeharto
and Croatian Prime Minister Zlatko Matesa held talks at the
Merdeka Palace.
</P>
<P>
"President Soeharto considers the counter-trade scheme as
beneficial to both sides," Moerdiono said, adding that Croatia
needs at least 1.5 million tons of coal per year.
</P>
<P>
On the trade sector, he said that Croatia offered to become
Indonesia's gateway for its products to East European countries.
</P>
<P>
Moerdiono also said Indonesia is considering the possibility of
helping bring the Croatians living in Australia back to their
country.
</P>
<P>
"There are about 250,000 Croatians living in Australia wishing
to return to their homeland," he said.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders today also witnessed the signing of agreements
on economic and technical cooperation and an aviation cooperation
agreement between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Matesa arrived here Wednesday for a five-day state visit to
Indonesia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
