<DOCNO> XIE19970227.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-27 15:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Book on Gulf War to Be Published in Kuwait </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, February 27 (Xinhua) -- A new book on the Gulf
War and the Kuwaiti resistance against the Iraqi occupation in
1990 would be published here as well as in Australia in March,
author John Levins said here today.
</P>
<P>
The Australian-Irish author said that his book "Days of Fear"
which runs 672 pages was "a comprehensive tapestry" covering
numerous aspects of Kuwait's struggle against Iraqi occupation
forces during the period.
</P>
<P>
It is so far the most comprehensive writing by a foreign
writer on how Kuwait's armed forces and people resisted the
aggression against their country.
</P>
<P>
Levins was resident in Kuwait when the invasion occurred on
August 2, 1990, and remained here until late December 1990.
</P>
<P>
He added that his prime motive for writing the book was to
"put balance into the story, show how in many ways the Kuwaiti
people and armed forces were instrumental in their own defense
and liberation" and refute a myth created by some news media
that "Kuwaitis sat in Cairo Hotels and paid western soldiers to
liberate them."
</P>
<P>
He said the book documented many hitherto unreported details
on how Kuwaitis resisted, organized military operations and
collected intelligence for the allied forces.
</P>
<P>
Levins pointed out that "a lot of this intelligence is
probably still classified."
</P>
<P>
In the book, there are also well-researched facts on
international diplomacy associated with the events, as well as
what happened to Kuwaitis under occupation.
</P>
<P>
The book also covers stories of a number of Kuwaitis who are
still missing as prisons of war (POWs) and foreign residents in
Kuwait, including Westerners and Arabs as well as Asians.
</P>
<P>
Levins sumed up the aim of his book as "to provide balance and
fill a gap in history." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
