<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Rail Disrupted by Suspected Anti-Nuclear Activists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Suspected anti-nuclear activists
continued to disrupt Germany's rail transport today ahead of a
planned controversial transport of nuclear waste.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here said that train services were seriously
affected in the northern German port city of Hamburg, with several
signal facilities being manipulated by people who, the police
said, had left behind leaflets mentioning the planned nuclear
transport.
</P>
<P>
In the state of Schleswig-Holstein, signal switch boxes at
railway crossings were fired, which disrupted commuter services to
nearby Hamburg.
</P>
<P>
The sabotages followed Tuesday attacks on overhead power lines
for electric trains in the states of Brandenburg, Berlin, Hesse,
Lower Saxony and Schleswig-Holstein, which stranded trains and
caused delays of up to three hours.
</P>
<P>
The latest nuclear transport is due to begin on Friday and to
reach a temporary underground storage depot at Gorleben, Lower
Saxony state, on March 2. The shipment includes four containers of
waste from nuclear power plants in southern Germany and three
others from the French nuclear recycling plant at La Hague.
</P>
<P>
The transport will be protected by 30,000 police and the
security cost is estimated around 100 million marks (60 million
U.S. dollars). The last such shipment costed 46 million marks
(27.6 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Violent protest over the planned nuclear transport has fueled
heated debate today in the parliament. Government parties accuse
the Greens Party of encouraging people against the rule of law and
as a result to undermine democracy.
</P>
<P>
The Greens warned against the possibly similar impact of the
1986 Chernobyl accident, saying nuclear radiation knew no
"borders."
</P>
<P>
The Greens and the Party of Democratic Socialism want a ban on
nuclear waste transports and have supported the recent mass
protest against the rail shipment of waste fuel rods from nuclear
power stations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
