<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britons Clone First Sheep Out of Frozen Cells </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 27 (Xinhua) -- British scientists created the
world's first cloned sheep out of frozen cells, which might lead
to recreating the dead from frozen tissue, local press reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Scientists cloned the sheep Dolly, the first animal
successfully created by non-sexual method, from frozen cells,
including a ewe's egg cell and a mammary gland cell taken from
another ewe, the firm sponsoring the research disclosed on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Scientists conceded that human cells frozen in controlled
conditions and protected with certain chemicals could possibly be
cloned, thus replicating a person.
</P>
<P>
This means that people who were deep frozen after death may one
day be brought back to life, reports said.
</P>
<P>
However, Ian Wilmut, head of the research team, denied on
Tuesday that he has taken science to the brink of cloning humans,
saying they are still nowhere near doing that.
</P>
<P>
He said the technique would undoubtly benefit humanity,
bringing in new fronts in fighting genetic diseases, such as AIDs.
</P>
<P>
The genetic breakthrough had immediately touched off a
controversy on what unethnic scientists might do with the
technique, such as using it to copy humans.
</P>
<P>
Liberal democrat legislator David Alton on Wednesday called on
the government to halt cloning experiments and start a public
debate on the issue.
</P>
<P>
However, Agriculture Minister Tony Baldry dismissed claims that
the cloning of animals could lead to farmyard mutants or assembly
lines of humans, saying it would instead help developments in
breeding and conservation.
</P>
<P>
"The reason the work has been done is that it makes selective
breeding more rapid, efficient and cost effective," Baldry
said. "It will be possible to breed livestock better adapted to
changing environments more quickly than previously possible."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
