<DOCNO> XIE19970227.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK's Trading Center Status to Remain Unchanged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's status as a
major trading center will not change in the near future and coming
years, said a report released by Standard Chartered Bank here
today.
</P>
<P>
It said the recent agreement between Taiwan and the Chinese
mainland to have direct shipping links between Fujian Province and
Kaohsiung will only have a very mild impact on Hong Kong's trade.
</P>
<P>
In the longer term, it said, if direct cross-strait trade
between the Chinese mainland and Taiwan is allowed, Hong Kong's
status as a major trading center will remain unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The report noted that direct shipping links between Taiwan and
the Chinese mainland will divert more trade from Hong Kong. It is
estimated that overall cross-strait re-exports and transshipment
trade handled through Hong Kong accounts for about 7.5 percent of
Hong Kong's total trade.
</P>
<P>
In later January, the shipping sectors of the Chinese mainland
and Taiwan reached consensus on technical issues concerning direct
shipping between the two selected ports of Fuzhou and Xiamen of
the Chinese mainland and the Kaohsiung Port in Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Start of such shipping services may divert some of the
transshipment trade currently handled by Hong Kong to Kaohsiung in
the future. However, the trade that will be affected is estimated
to be small, as Xiamen and Fuzhou are relatively small ports.
</P>
<P>
In the longer term, the report said, there will also be new
trading opportunities for Hong Kong as the vast central and
western provinces and regions on the Chinese mainland are growing
with a gradual shift in the Chinese government's preferential
policies toward the inland areas.
</P>
<P>
It said that for many of these provinces, Hong Kong is
geographically a more convenient port than most of the ports along
China's coasts.
</P>
<P>
It said the operation of the Beijing-Kowloon Railway will
further enhance Hong Kong's status as a trading center.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
