<HEADLINE> 5.5-Percent Growth Forecast for HK GDP in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong Financial
Secretary Donald Tsang said today that Hong Kong's GDP is expected
to have a growth of 5.5 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
In his Budget Prelude Speech to the Hong Kong Investment Funds
Association, Tsang said Hong Kong would start life as a Special
Administrative Region of China in sound economic shape, with every
prospect of remaining the most attractive business location in the
region.
</P>
<P>
He said the forecast GDP growth rate is about the right,
sustainable level for Hong Kong's mature economy.
</P>
<P>
"This would give us another year of solid economic performance,
with growth very much in line with our medium-term forecast of 5
percent."
</P>
<P>
He expected the economy to perform better in foreign trade and
the growth rate of private consumption expenditure to pick up to
5.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
"Unemployment will remain low. Stronger earnings and a tighter
labor market will boost consumer confidence," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said Hong Kong's status as a Special Administrative Region
will create new trade and investment opportunities as the
modernization process continues to transform the Chinese economy.
</P>
<P>
"We forecast that Hong Kong's exports of services will grow by
8 percent. Total exports of goods will grow by 8.5 percent," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He said inflation for 1997 is expected to rise at a somewhat
higher rate than last year and an average increase of 7 percent is
forecast.  
</P>
