<DOCNO> XIE19970227.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Discovery Shows Sophisticated Lifestyle in Northern Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Three 400,000-year-old spears,
the oldest complete hunting weapons found to date, have been
unearthed in Germany, indicating the earliest northern Europeans
were sophisticated hunters.
</P>
<P>
The spruce spears, the largest of which is seven feet long and
about two inches wide, were surrounded by the butchered remains of
at least 14 horses, archaeologist Dr. Hartmut Thieme of the
Institute of Denkmalpflege reported in today's science journal
Nature.
</P>
<P>
The site, now an open-cast coal mine, was probably a hunting
station at the edge of a lake where hunters sharpened their tools,
cut up the meat of horses and other large animals such as rhinos,
and possibly cooked it over rough hearths.
</P>
<P>
At the time, said Dr. Thieme, Europe was coming to the end of
an interglacial period and the climate would have been comparable
to that of central Norway today -- relatively cold with meadows and
forests.
</P>
<P>
The discovery of the spears destroys current theories that the
first humans to colonize northern Europe were opportunistic
scavengers who were only capable of reacting to
circumstances. Until now, humans were thought to have had very
primitive lifestyles before the emergence of art and finely-honed
tools about 40,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
But this new evidence suggests that, 10 times earlier than
that, they were planning hunting expeditions in advance and
meticulously crafting weapons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970227.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Officials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Indian officials said today
that the reported hijacking of an Indian plane earlier in the day
was actually a "mock hijack" to test the security system.
</P>
<P>
The hijack turned out to be a "mock exercise" to test the
response of the security drill and the aircraft returned to the
Delhi airport safely later, they said.
</P>
<P>
The Press Trust of India (PTI) earlier reported that a private
plane of Alliance Airliner, a subsidiary of Indian Airlines, was
hijacked by some unidentified men with 36 passengers aboard on a
flight from the capital New Delhi to India-held Jammu.
</P>
<P>
An assessment would be made on the response of the system in
all areas later, the officials said. The aircraft was being kept
at an isolated bay.  
</P>
