<HEADLINE> Newspaper Commentary To Mark Taiwan's "February 28 Uprising" (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 27 (Xinhua) -- A commentary to be carried in
Friday's People's Daily, marking the 50th anniversary of Taiwan's
"February 28 Uprising," calls on the Chinese people to carry
forward the patriotic and democratic spirit and promote the
peaceful reunification of the motherland,
</P>
<P>
The commentary expresses deep sorrow for those who died in the
uprising 50 years ago and extends warm regards to the broad masses
of Taiwan compatriots.
</P>
<P>
The "February 28 Uprising" was launched by the people of Taiwan
in 1947, in response to Chiang Kai-Shek's intransigence. The
action eventually led to an armed struggle.
</P>
<P>
The uprising was the first large-scale patriotic and democratic
movement initiated by the Taiwan people to resist the Kuomintang's
autocratic rule since the recovery of sovereignty over Taiwan in
1945, which followed the victory of the War of Resistance against
the Japanese Aggression. The uprising was also an important
component of the whole nation's opposition to the autocratic rule
of the Kuomintang government, it says.
</P>
<P>
The patriotic and democratic spirit displayed by the Taiwan
compatriots in the "February 28 Uprising" will last forever in the
Chinese history, it says, noting any fabrication of charges and
distortion against it are in vain.
</P>
<P>
Historical records of first-hand accounts of the uprising have
irrefutably proved that its main objective was to fight corruption
and demand democracy and autonomy, but there was no recorded
evidence to suggest the demand for establishing an independent
country, the commentary says.
</P>
<P>
However, it says, in an attempt to crack down on the uprising,
the Kuomintang government invented a groundless charge that the
uprising was "revolting against the motherland." This is vicious
slander, it says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970227.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Newspaper Commentary To Mark Taiwan's "February 28 Uprising" (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
From then on, it notes, certain forces on the island that have
advocated the "independence of Taiwan" have tried every means to
label the uprising an "exclusive" or "Taiwan independence"
movement, alleging that the "February 28 Uprising" was the
beginning of the "Taiwan independence" movement.
</P>
<P>
"This is a sheer blasphemy and insult against the Taiwan
compatriots involved in the uprising and a wanton distortion of
the facts," the commentary says.
</P>
<P>
It should be noted, it says, that some of the Taiwan
authorities have allied themselves with the forces promoting
"Taiwan independence" by advocating the "doctrine of new
Taiwanese." Their purpose is to separate the interest of the
Taiwan people from that of the whole Chinese nation and create a
conflict between them, so as to mislead the Taiwan compatriots
down the road of splitting the island from China, the commentary
adds.
</P>
<P>
"But we firmly believe that the broad masses of the Taiwan
people are able to see through and fight the malicious political
plot," it says.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Communist Party and government have always
understood, respected, trusted and relied on the Taiwan
compatriots, it says, adding that it is necessary to consult with
the Taiwan compatriots when handling the Taiwan issue, to take the
interest of the Taiwan people into consideration and to respect
their lifestyles and wish of "being real masters of Taiwan."
</P>
<P>
After a peaceful reunification of the motherland in accordance
with the concept of "one country, two system," Taiwan will enjoy a
high degree of autonomy within the framework of China as one
country, it says.
</P>
<P>
This not only meets the demand for democracy and autonomy
expressed by the Taiwan people half a century ago, but also is in
line with the wish of the Taiwanese to become the real masters of
the island, the commentary says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
