<DOCNO> XIE19970227.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia, Thailand to Settle Border Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, February 27 (Xinhua) -- The prime ministers of
Malaysia and Thailand today agreed to solve their two countries'
problem of border demarcation within two months.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir Mohamad and visiting Chavalit Yongchaiyudh reached the
agreement during their talks here today, Malaysian Foreign
Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi told a news conference after the
talks.
</P>
<P>
The problem has been discussed at different levels, "but now
the principle has been established and the problem of border
demarcation will be resolved within two months or 60 days," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"The principle is that in deciding this border demarcation
where you have the border involving rivers and the rivers keep
shifting because of floods, it is important to have a permanent
border not to be affected by the shifting of the rivers and there
should be a principle of No Gain No Loss, Win-Win situation," he
added.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders agreed that there should be more activities
along the border and joint development approaches adopted to
benefit both countries, Abdullah said.
</P>
<P>
A land bridge linking the two countries also came up for
discussion between the two prime ministers.
</P>
<P>
They also touched on the sale of gas by a Malaysian company to
Thailand, the foreign minister said.
</P>
<P>
Agreeing that there are very good relations between two
countries, the two prime ministers would like to see the bilateral
relations continue to improve especially in areas of trade and
mutual investment, Abdullah said.
</P>
<P>
They agreed therefore that a joint committee on trade and a
joint business council will be formed, hoping that they would
help increase trade between the two countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
Trade between Malaysia and Thailand has been growing steadily
from 3.8 billion U.S. dollars in 1994 to 4.9 billion dollars last
year.
</P>
<P>
Answering a question about illegal immigration along the
Malaysian-Thai border, the foreign minister said the leaders did
not discuss this.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of the enlargement of ASEAN, of which both
Malaysia and Thailand are members, Abdullah said there was no talk
on the issue between Mahathir and Chavalit.
</P>
<P>
Chavalit arrived here earlier today for a two-day official
visit to Malaysia at the invitation of Mahathir.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
