<HEADLINE> Arabs Urge UN Emergency Meeting on Israeli </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Arab countries have asked the
United Nations Security Council to convene an emergency session
to challenge Israel's new housing plan in East Jerusalem,
Palestinian U.N. representative Nasser al-Qodwa said today.
</P>
<P>
Most members of the Security Council are ready to confront
Israel's settlement activity, he told Voice of Arab radio of
Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Denouncing the Israeli decision to build new Jewish housing
units in East Jerusalem, the Palestinian official said Jerusalem
is an Arab city, which will "remain Arab eternally."
</P>
<P>
"Its status will never be determined by statements voiced by
Israel's Prime Minister (Binyamin Netanyahu)," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli Ministerial Committee on Jerusalem Affairs
approved Wednesday the construction of 6,500 housing units in
Har Homa settlement, a tree-covered hill taken by Israel in the
1967 Mideast War. Another 3,000 homes would be built for Arabs.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Arab League Secretary-General Esmat Abdul-Meguid
Wednesday night denounced the measure, saying that it is aimed at
Judaizing the holy city and creating a fait accompli to preempt
the peace talks on final status in March.
</P>
<P>
He called for a unified Arab stance in the face of this
"dangerous" attitude of Israel, which he described as an act
defying the international community. 
</P>
</TEXT>
