<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Military Vessels on Visit to Three Southeast Asian Nations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Two Chinese military ships
weighed anchor here this afternoon, on the start of visits to
Thailand, Malaysia and the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
The vessels, guided missile destroyer No. 113 and guided
missile corvette No. 542, were led by Vice Admiral Yang Yushu,
commander of the East China Sea Fleet of the Chinese People's
Liberation Army (PLA).
</P>
<P>
This is the second overseas visit by the PLA navy within a
week. On February 20, a formation left for four American countries
of the United States, Mexico, Peru and Chile. The current journey
will cover a total of nearly 7,000 nautical miles.
</P>
<P>
Prior to departure, Yang told reporters that Chinese naval
vessels have made trips to southeast Asian nations four times.
</P>
<P>
The "Zhenghe" ocean training ship of the PLA navy sailed to
Thailand in 1990 and 1993. The current trip marks the first time
for PLA navy vessels to visit Malaysia and the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
According to Yang, the development of friendly relations with
neighboring nations has always been a priority of the Chinese
military's foreign exchanges.
</P>
<P>
In 1985, he said, the destination of the first official visit
of the PLA navy was three south Asian nations -- Pakistan, Sri
Lanka and Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
Yang said these visits increased the friendly relations and
understanding between these countries and China, as well as their
armed forces and the PLA.
</P>
<P>
The PLA naval vessels have made a total of 11 trips to 14
countries, eight of which are in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
Vice Admiral Shi Yunsheng, commander of the PLA navy, and other
Chinese military and government officials saw Yang and his fleet
off. 
</P>
</TEXT>
