<HEADLINE> Albright's Visit Propelled Sino-US Ties: Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 27 (Xinhua) -- US Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright's recent visit to China was helpful for
maintaining the development momentum of Sino-US relations, Chinese
Foreign Ministry Spokesman Tang Guoqiang said here today.
</P>
<P>
Responding to a question at a routine press conference, Tang
said that during Albright's stay in China both sides deepened
their mutual understanding through discussions on Sino-US
relations, and international and regional issues of common concern.
</P>
<P>
"With joint efforts from both sides," he noted, "bilateral
relations have witnessed development recently."
</P>
<P>
President Jiang Zemin and President Clinton defined the
principles for further improvement of Sino-US relations in Manila
in November last year, and the two leaders will exchange state
visits this year and next, according to Tang.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, US Vice-President Al Gore will soon visit China at
the invitation of Premier Li Peng, and bilateral ties now face a
new opportunity for improvement, he noted.
</P>
<P>
"China is willing to strengthen dialogue and co-operation with
the US," the spokesman said. "Meanwhile, China hopes that the US
side will strictly observe the principles set out in the three
Sino-US joint communiques, and handle the Taiwan issue in a
cautious and proper way so as to keep the development momentum of
bilateral ties."  
</P>
