<HEADLINE> Hussein, Arafat Talk on Jerusalem Jewish </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, February 27 (Xinhua) -- King Hussein of Jordan, in a
telephone conversations today, exchanged views with
Palestinian President Yasser Arafat on the Israeli decision to
construct new Jewish settlements in the Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
They also discussed the impact of the Israeli approval of new
settlements on the Middle East peace process, Radio Jordan
reported.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders agreed to follow up closely with the situation
in a bid to push forward the peace march.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli government Wednesday formally approved the
construction of the Har Homa new Jewish settlement of some 6,500
housing units in East Jerusalem despite strong opposition by the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) and other Arab States.
</P>
<P>
Hussein has urged Israel to reconsider its decision on
approving the new housing plan in the controversial city, saying
that it would fuel anger which could threaten the peace
negotiations in the region.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu
recently, the Jordanian king said that the decision was bound to
shake the credibility of the peace process as a whole and fuel
anger which would create violence.
</P>
<P>
He said that Jordan considers East Jerusalem as a Palestinian
territory occupied by Israel and any change to its status
unilaterally before reaching a final agreement with the PNA
constitutes a real danger to peace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
