<HEADLINE> Nigerian Cashew Nut Delegation Set for India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria will soon send a
delegation to India to promote its export of cashew nut, the
"Guardian" reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report said the delegation comprising of government
officials and members of the Cashew Trade Association of Nigeria
(CASHTAN) will leave for India next month, before the start of
the new season.
</P>
<P>
India buys 95 percent of Nigeria's cashew nut exports.
However, the report said, Nigerian cashew nut has a reputation of
poor quality, so it can sell only at low prices at the
international market.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, Nigerian cashew nut sold for only 500 to 600 U.S.
Dollars a ton on free-on-board terms, compared to 1,200 Dollars a
ton for those from Tanzania, Mozambique, Indonesia, Guinea Bissau
and Brazil.
</P>
<P>
This led to a loss of one billion Naira (about 12.5 million
Dollars) to Nigerian exporters, the report said.
</P>
<P>
It added that the delegation will try to convince Indian
importers of the improved quality of Nigerian cashew nut and
secure immediate orders against the new season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
