<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Efforts Made to Put Out Fire at Paradip Port </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Hectic efforts are being
made by Paradip Port Trust Authorities in India's eastern state of
Orissa to put out a big fire which has engulfed a huge stock of
coal near the cargo berth of the port, the Press Trust of India
(PTI) said here today.
</P>
<P>
Fifteen-meter-high flames have so far consumed about 10,000
tons of coal and thick smoke has filled up the area for the last
couple of days.
</P>
<P>
About 160,000 tons of coal, kept in four piles, were to be
shipped to Tamil Nadu to meet the needs of the thermal power
station there.
</P>
<P>
The Paradip port had never piled up such a large quantity of
coal before. The arrival of more coal from the Talcher collieries
due to the availability of more railway wagons and a sharp
decrease in ships available for transporting the coal to Tamil
Nadu had resulted in the pileup, the PTI quoted the Port Trust
Authorities as saying.
</P>
<P>
No cause has been given for the fire.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
