<DOCNO> XIE19970227.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-27 11:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: New Dispute in Jerusalem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of policemen have
been brought into Jerusalem today to deal with possible violence
stemming from the Israeli government's decision to build a new
Jewish neighborhood in the city.
</P>
<P>
The ministerial committee on Jerusalem, headed by Prime
Minister Binyamin Netanyahu, approved the controversial plan
Wednesday to build 6,500 Jewish homes, in addition to
construction of 3,015 units for Arabs in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian officials reacted angrily to the building plan,
saying the Israeli government's decision is a violation of law
and its agreements with the Palestinians, and has put the
peace process in danger.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) President Yasser Arafat
called on the UN Security Council and the Arab League to
help stop the construction in Har Homa.
</P>
<P>
Arafat, who returned from a meeting of the Higher Jerusalem
committee in Morocco Wednesday, said before his return, "The
attempt to settle on Jabal Abu Ghneim (Har Homa) is an
attempt to surround Jerusalem."
</P>
<P>
PNA Secretary Ahmed Abud Rahman said that Arafat is very
worried about the peace process, warning that a new conflict over
Jerusalem could spark uncontrolled violence.
</P>
<P>
Faisal Husseini, PNA official on Jerusalem affairs, told
Israel Radio that what he smells in the air is Intifada
(uprising), the same as he did just after the opening of the
Western Wall tunnel exit last September.
</P>
<P>
The opening of the tunnel had led to a serious violent
confrontation between Israeli soldiers and Palestinian policemen,
which left over 70 dead and hundreds of others wounded.
</P>
<P>
Palestinians are fearing that a Jewish-dominated Har Homa will
cut the link between the self-rule areas in the West Bank and Arab
sections in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Har Homa is located in the middle of the one large undeveloped
area of Jerusalem in the southeast, which links Bethlehem to Abu
Dis. But its location is described differently by the Israeli and
Palestinian sides to emphasize their own respective surroundings.
</P>
<P>
Abu Dis is mentioned in an Israeli-Palestinian proposal as the
major part of a future sovereign Palestinian Jerusalem and
therefore is a crucial element in permanent status talks.
</P>
<P>
Israeli High Court of Justice rejected appeals by both Jewish
and Arab landowners and approved expropriations, and the Peace
Now, an Israeli left-wing group, has said that it will once again
challenge the construction in the High Court.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian objections to the Har Homa project go beyond the
simple fact that it is built on land Israel seized from Jordan in
the 1967 war and therefore constitutes in their eyes an illegal
settlement.
</P>
<P>
In the long run, Har Homa is seen as one unit in a string of
Jewish neighborhoods planned across south Jerusalem, starting
north of Gilo with Givat Matos, east to Givat Arba, on to Har Homa
and continuing to Havat Mazmoriya.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the housing for Arabs is to be spread out
among 10 other neighborhoods which are not in politically crucial
locations.
</P>
<P>
The Jewish population in east Jerusalem is 165,000, according
to Israeli sources, while the Arab population is 161,000. "So if
Israel builds this big neighborhood we have a larger Jewish
majority there," said Halil Tufakji, a cartographer who advises
the PNA.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the final status Israel had in mind takes clear
shape with the Har Homa project. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970227.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
