<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Bans Licensing of New Saw Mills </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, February 27 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government has
temporarily banned the licensing of new saw mills countrywide in
a bid to reduce further depletion of forest resources.
</P>
<P>
During a recent tour of forest land in Rift Valley Province,
Minister for the Environment and Natural Resources Henry Kosgey
said that the high number of saw mills was to blame for the rapid
depletion of valuable forest resources in many parts of the
country.
</P>
<P>
He noted that his ministry received 292 applications last
year from individuals who wanted to venture in the saw-milling
business, but only half of them were approved.
</P>
<P>
The minister stressed that the high number of saw mills had
caused forests to "disappear at an alarming rate" without a
corresponding move to plant more trees.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Kenyan farmers were directed to stop burning their
fields so as to reduce the high rate of forest fires which
have destroyed large tracts of forests in the east African
country.
</P>
<P>
According to local press reports, forest fires have been
raging in Mount Kenya, Mount Elgon, Keiyo and Makueni areas.
</P>
<P>
Fires in the northern part of Mount Kenya have caused damage
to vegetation stretching for about 20 square kilometers and
indigenous cedar and olive forests, hundreds of acres of softwood
plantation and manure trees have been destroyed.
</P>
<P>
In Nakuru District, fierce fire is raging in Tiret, Neswit and
Marioshoni forests, destroying more than 500 hectares of forests
on the Menengai Hill and its environs near Nakuru Town, about 165
kilometers northwest of Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
Government officials attributed the wide-spreading forest
fires in the country mainly to the burning of farm fields in
preparation for the coming planting season. enditem

=02271038

=02271044
NNNN
18:44 18:45 g # PAB
