<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-27 10:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNA Condemns Israeli Decision on Housing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, February 27 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian National
Authority issues a statement in Gaza Wednesday night strongly
condemning Israeli government's decision to go ahead with
construction of a new Jewish settlement at Har Homa in the Arab
East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The statement was released at the end of an urgent meeting
presided over by Palestinian President Yasser Arafat, according
to a report of JMCC, a Palestinian press service based in East
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli Ministerial Committee on Jerusalem Affairs decided
Wednesday evening to approve the construction of Har Homa
Settlement. Some 6,500 housing units will be built in the
settlement and the first stage will include some 2,500 units.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that the decision constitutes a violation
of international law and of the Israel-PLO peace agreements.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian Cabinet Secretary, Ahmed Abdel Rahman, warned
that a new conflict over Jerusalem could spark uncontrollable
violence.
</P>
<P>
Arafat's senior aide Marwan Kalafani told reporters that
Arafat is upset by the Israeli decision and worried about the
future of the peace process. But he would do whatever he can to
get back the peace process on track.
</P>
<P>
Arafat held telephone consultations on the implications of
the Har Homa issue with King Hussein of Jordan and President
Hosni Mubarak of Egypt. He also sent a letter to U.S. President
Bill Clinton on the issue, which is expected to be high on
agenda during his meeting with Clinton at the White House next
week.
</P>
<P>
Jerusalem is the most sensitive issue of the Arab-Israeli
conflict. According to the Oslo Accords, the issue will be
discussed in the final stage talks. Neither side should take
unilateral steps to change the status quo before that.
</P>
<P>
As tensions are mounting, the Israeli army and police have
beefed up their forces in Jerusalem and elsewhere in the West
Bank. Some 500 extra police were sent to East Jerusalem to help
crack down any possible violent resistance from the
Palestinians, according to Israel Radio. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
