<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Transnational Cooperation in Science Benefits Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Transnational scientific
cooperation has yielded positive results in Shanghai, the leading
industrial and commercial center in China.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai Metallurgical Research Institute recently joined
hands with the Ericsson Corp of Sweden to set up the Shanghai
Ericsson Xin Tai Electronics Company. Total investment in the
project was 6.2 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-four transnational companies have been set up jointly by
15 local research institutes and corporations in the United
States, Germany, Japan and Britain, to co-develop hi-tech products.
</P>
<P>
These foreign-funded companies, with total capital of 100
million US dollars, scored 375 million yuan in sales last year,
and 36 million US dollars in foreign exchange through export,
respectively 58 percent and 46 percent up over 1995.
</P>
<P>
The newly-developed technological products range from
biological medicine, electronic items, integrated circuit to
hormone products. And the sales of infrared sensors co-produced by
Shanghai and Japan reportedly have occupied 60 percent of the
world market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
