<HEADLINE> Vietnam Aims for 100,000 Milk Cows in 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam is planning to increase
the number of milk cows from 32,000 presently to 100,000 in 2000,
bringing the output of milk to 80,000 tons, the Ministry of
Agriculture and Rural Development said here today.
</P>
<P>
The ministry has called on domestic and foreign businessmen to
invest in a dairy project involving 46 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Ho Chi Minh city has the biggest dairy herd in the country with
27,500 milk cows raised in suburban districts and 7,600 heads
yielding 70-80 tons of milk per day.
</P>
<P>
The city's Sai Gon Milk Company has invested 15 million U.S.
dollars in a project to help local farmers increase the number of
milk cows to 25,000.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnamese government has also signed an agreement on aid
of 4.2 million dollars from Belgium for a 5-million-dollar project
on the development and expansion of dairy industry in vietnam.
</P>
<P>
This project, to be carried on in five years, will develop
dairying in eight Hanoi outlying districts and some districts
adjacent to Hanoi in Vinh Phuc province, as well as in southern
Vietnam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
