<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, February 27 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- The French National Assembly is expected to adopt the
strongly contested new immigration law, after deputies of the
ruling majority have softened their position on immigration, while
the film-makers, who initiated the civil disobedience movement
against the law, said their objectives have been attained.
</P>
<P>
-- The decision by Israeli government to build a new Jewish
settlement in the Har-Homa district in East Jerusalem has aroused
condemnation from Amman to Washington, while the Palestinian
authority has asked the United Nations Security Council to stop
the Israeli plan.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- According to the official statistics bureau, the INSEE,
50,387 foreigners immigrated under legal procedures to France in
1995, a drop from 64,100 in 1994, 94,152 in 1993 and 110,669 in
1992.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, 11 percent of the babies born in France were from
immigrant families, most of them North African, black African and
Turkish immigrants.
</P>
<P>
-- The birth of Dolly, the world's first mammal lamb cloned
from an adult lamb, is a beautiful scientific performance and
should not be regarded as a simply sensational event, said
Francois Jacob, the 1962 winner of Nobel Prize in Medicine.
</P>
<P>
He said that to manipulate genetic heritage of animals to
produce hormones and make "humanized" organs is better than raise
battery chicken. 
</P>
</TEXT>
