<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 4.2 Million Short-Term Visitors Come To Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, February 27 (Xinhua) -- The number of short-term
visitors to Australia rose to a record 4.2 million last year, with
about 79 percent of them coming for holidays or visits to friends
and 9 percent for business.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Bureau of Statistics said today that tourism
operators expressed their concerns over an apparent loss of the
country's share of the growing tourism market in Japan, whose
813,100 visitors accounted for 20 percent of the total visitors to
Australia.
</P>
<P>
The number of visitors from New Zealand, the second biggest
market for Australian tourism, jumped dramatically by 25 percent
to 671,900 and visitors from the third major source country, the
United Kingdom, also increased by 6 percent to 367,500.
</P>
<P>
There was also growth in other major markets -- Korea by 36
percent, Singapore by 10 percent and the United States by 4
percent.
</P>
<P>
The number of Australians going overseas for short trips also
went up last year by 8 percent to about 2.51 million.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
