<DOCNO> XIE19970227.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Four Cambodian Parties Form Coalition Prior to Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Four Cambodian parties
today officially launched the National United Front (NUF) in
preparation for the legislative elections due to be held in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The political alliance groups the currently biggest ruling
FUNCINPEC Party led by First Prime Minister Norodom Ranariddh, the
Khmer Neutral Party led by Bour Hel, the Khmer Nation Party (KNP)
led by Sam Rainsy and a faction of the split Buddhist Liberal
Democratic led by Son Sann.
</P>
<P>
"The NUF respects and defends the Monarchy, the Constitution of
1993 and its national motto: Nation, Religion, King," said a
program on NUF's political beliefs and objectives proclaimed at a
founding conference.
</P>
<P>
According to the program, the NUF will establish legislative
state system, make administration and the armed forces stay
neutral, defend human rights, fight against dictatorship, promote
international cooperation, and absolutely defend the national
sovereignty and territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
"The NUF will not create nor allow regional secession even
having lost the elections," the program declares.
</P>
<P>
The program also said that the NUF stands for having one prime
minister in the future government instead of having co-prime
ministers as at present.
</P>
<P>
The founding of the NUF is not against any other party or
political forces, but is aimed at regrouping patriotic
personalities from various parties to ensure the political
stability, said Ranariddh, who was elected president of the
alliance.
</P>
<P>
Ranariddh also said the NUF enjoyed full support from the
National Democratic United Movement headed by Ieng Sary who led a
splinter group from Khmer Rouge and change-over to the government
last August.
</P>
<P>
Son Sann, whose party has only one seat in the current
parliament, noted that each party within the front must keep its
own identity and independence.
</P>
<P>
KNP president Sam Rainsy appealed for close cooperation between
the four parties and indicated that every important decision by
the NUF must be made through the consensus system.
</P>
<P>
The biggest rival of the NUF is the second biggest ruling
Cambodian People's Party headed by Second Prime Minister Hun Sen
who formed a coalition government with Ranariddh in 1993 after
U.N.-run elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970227.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-27 11:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian Forces Destroy Drug Fields </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, February 26 (Xinhua) -- The Egyptian armed forces
uprooted large stretch of fields cultivated with bango and poppy
spread over 1,500 feddans (630 hectares) in the eastern Sinai
mountainous areas and valleys.
</P>
<P>
The attack came after an air survey conducted early February
spotted the illegal plantations, the Egyptian MENA news agency
quoted Major General Samir Youssef, commander of the border guard
forces, as saying Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Field armies, the shock troops and chemical warfare units
alongside police forces, which were engaged in the operation
started on February 14, relied on different axes to destroy the
unlawful cultivations which would make a big produce.
</P>
<P>
Youssef said there were no clashes with the owners of the
farms, who had got the wind and fled the area.
</P>
<P>
The poppy, cultivated in November and harvested in March, is
used in making opium and heroin as well as morphine. Bango is
harvested four times during the year.
</P>
<P>
The campaign was decreed by Minister of Defense Field Marshal
Hussein Tantawi who instructed the authorities concerned to
continue the fight against the dirty trade of narcotics and
pursue moves to frustrate the schemes of drug traffickers.
</P>
<P>
A similar campaign last year led to the destruction of 6,000
feddans (2,520 hectares) of poppy and 8,000 feddans (3,360
hectares) of bango.
</P>
<P>
Air survey indicated that these illegal plantations are
concentrated in 18 valleys in southern Sinai, the same locations
as last year's cultivations of poppy and bango.
</P>
<P>
The armed forces used highly-advanced equipment and certain
chemicals to destroy the plantations but these chemicals do not
harm the environment as the soil gets clean once rain falls, the
commander said.
</P>
<P>
He said that so far 924 poppy and 452 bango plantations at a
total area of 420 hectares, were destroyed. The operation will
continue until all the illegal plantations are routed, he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the forces have seized 274 kilograms of dried bango,
85 kilograms of bango seeds and 81 kilograms of poppy seeds
together with some explosives and rifles, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
