<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Develops Video Games to Teach Patriotism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 27 (Xinhua) -- China is making efforts to
develop its own video games for eduction in patriotism.
</P>
<P>
Foreign-made video games dominate 98 percent of the Chinese
market. Among the imported games, 70 percent advocate violence,
terrorism and greed, around five percent contain pornographic
material, and three percent promote Nazism and militarism, or
emphasize the superiority of western weapons, according to a
survey conducted on Chinese players by Qinghua University.
</P>
<P>
Tian Yong, president of the prestigious Beijing Fourth
Secondary School, says he worries that more and more urban
secondary school students have become addicted to video games. In
colleges and universities, many dormitories have bought computers,
the majority of which are used for recreational purposes such as
game-playing.
</P>
<P>
China's development of video game software is still in its
infancy, and such games have long been overlooked as an
educational tool that could promote cultural and ethical progress,
said one software designer.
</P>
<P>
"We grow up with books and movies, but children born since the
1980s have been educated partly by computers and video games,"
Tian said, adding that teachers and parents are worried that
children will be too easily influenced by what some Chinese
believe to be inappropriate material included in the games.
</P>
<P>
"It is impossible to prevent them from playing video games," he
said. "The best thing we can do is to provide them with good
games."
</P>
<P>
Over the past few years, video enthusiasts nationwide have
been writing to the Optical Memory National Engineering Research
Center of Qinghua University, urging the facility to develop
interesting games that can instill patriotism in the users. The
center is a high-tech research base designed to solve the major
technological problems in the publication of optical discs.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of 1996, the center invested two million
yuan to develop video games with a patriotic theme. The first
group, including games titled "Opium War," "August 1 Fighting
Eagle," "Long March," will appear on the market later this year.
</P>
<P>
The game "Opium War" will be issued in recognition of the
return of Hong Kong to the motherland in July. The game simulates
the war between more than 40 Chinese and British military
officers, including Lin Zexu, whose ban on opium trade touched off
the historic Opium War between China and Britain from
1840-1842. The war resulted the ceding of Hong Kong to Britain.
</P>
<P>
Lu Da, vice director of the research center, said that though
China lost the war in history, players of the games can get a
sense of government corruption during the Qing Dynasty, and gain a
better understanding of the historical background of the Opium War
and the impact of the war on the development of modern China,
thereby inspiring patriotism for modern-day China.
</P>
<P>
"August 1 Fighting Eagle" represents the story of Wang Hai and
other Chinese pilots who downed more than 300 US fighter planes in
the Korean war.
</P>
<P>
The "Long March" game simulates the victory of the Long March
(1934-36) by the Red Army, which trekked through more than a dozen
provinces and cities, and helped to lay a solid foundation for the
founding of New China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970227.0158 </DOCNO>
