<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UAE to Ban Foodstuff With British Cow Gelatin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, February 27 (Xinhua) -- The United Arab Emirates
(UAE) is to withdraw foodstuff and sweets containing beef gelatin
of British origin from local markets and ban the import of such
items, a local newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The ban was declared by the General Secretariat of UAE
Municipalities secretariat in its 46th session held in Sharjah,
one of the seven emirates of the country, Wednesday, according to
the "Khaleej Time" newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The UAE has already stopped the import of British and Irish
beef since the outbreak of the Bovine Spongiform Encephalitis
(BSE) in Europe last year. The BSE, commonly known as the
mad cow disease, is said to affect the human beings as the
Creutzfeld-Jakobs disease.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile the secretariat considers to lift ban on Irish beef
in accordance with the regulations and restrictions agreed upon
between the Irish authorities and the UAE, said the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The secretariat said it will keep a close watch and regularly
test samples of the Irish beef to ensure that it is suitable for
the local market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
