<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Service Trade Generating More Added Value for North China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, February 27 (Xinhua) -- The service trade
generated 109 billion yuan in added value for the north China
province of Hebei in 1996, a rise of 11 percent over the previous
year.
</P>
<P>
Service trade has become a leading factor in advancing the
growth of the province's economy, said local officials. It has
offered jobs to seven million people, or 20 percent of the
province's total workforce.
</P>
<P>
The officials attributed the success of the past year to the
province's concerted efforts to make full use of its advantageous
location on the border of Beijing and Tianjin.
</P>
<P>
Hebei is now a transportation hub and an important center for
collection and distribution of commodities.
</P>
<P>
According to a development plan for the service trade during
the Ninth Five-Year-Plan period (1996-2000), the province will
construct 10 modern shopping plazas, each having a floor space of
50,000 sq m, as well as 100 medium-sized shopping markets by the
year of 2000.
</P>
<P>
Guided by the plan, the province has already built a group of
wholesale markets for farm produce, industrial consumer products
and means of production.
</P>
<P>
It also plans to build 60 large circulation enterprise groups
involving in trading of commodities including cereals and oils,
petroleum and medicine.
</P>
<P>
While vigorously developing tourism and real estate, the
province will also earmark more money for the development of
information services and the establishment of a great number of
intermediary service organizations in the years to come, said
local officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
