<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Opposition to Launch Protest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, February 27 (Xinhua) -- The main opposition Bangladesh
Nationalist Party (BNP) will stage demonstrations across the
country on March 3 to mark the launching of its fresh agitation
against the eight-month-old government.
</P>
<P>
BNP Chairperson and former Prime Minister Khaleda Zia announced
the plan at a huge public meeting in Feni City, 136 kilometers
southeast of the capital, Dhaka, yesterday.
</P>
<P>
"This is the beginning of our program. We are starting from
here, and it will continue all over the country," Zia told the
gathering of thousands of people of her paternal home district.
</P>
<P>
This was her first public meeting after the debacle of the BNP
in the parliamentary elections last June.
</P>
<P>
Though there was no incident at the meeting venue, a series of
acts of violence took place in different parts of the district, in
which more than 50 BNP activists were injured.
</P>
<P>
Zia warned her political opponents that whenever they launch
any attack, it would be resisted.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina's request not to
launch any agitation, the opposition leader said: "We have not
given any tough program, but will be compelled to go for it in
future."
</P>
<P>
She said that despite its willingness, her party could not
cooperate with the government which she charged was "selling out"
the country's interests and "violating" the constitution.
</P>
<P>
"Let's save the country, its independence and sovereignty,
democracy, constitution, and people's life and property," she
said.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Hasina warned early this month that the
opposition should seriously think before taking up any agitation
program.
</P>
<P>
"They might try to create some problem, even break some
vehicles, but won't succeed," she added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
