<HEADLINE> Liaoning Province Optimizes Property Structure of State Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, February 27 (Xinhua) -- In 1996, Liaoning Province in
northeast China quickened its pace of optimizing the property
structure of local state-owned enterprises through annexation,
bankruptcy and listing, according to local officials.
</P>
<P>
The state firms involved had activated a large amount of
property worth 5.2 billion yuan and reduced losses valued at 2.2
billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Substantial achievements were made by cities of Shenyang,
Dalian, Anshan, Fushun and Benxi, which are among the country's
110 pilot cities to experiment with the practice.
</P>
<P>
Last year, 80 enterprises were merged and 133 firms went
bankrupt in these five cities, which resulted in 226,000 layoffs,
while 197,000 jobless workers were rehired through the
government's reemployment programs.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the debt-ratio of state firms in the five cities had
decreased from 71.5 percent in the first half of last year to 65.7
percent in the second half.
</P>
<P>
Also last year, the province set up 32 large enterprise groups
and, 1,333 small companies had been reformed in various
forms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
