<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East China Province Making Better Use of Imported Technology </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Over the past six years, the provincial government invited 400
experts from the United States, Germany, France, and Japan to
assist in 300 research projects, generating additional profits of
500 million yuan (60.2 million US dollars) in the process.
</P>
<P>
Rice-growing specialists from Japan have introduced dry-farming
and sparse-cultivation techniques that save labor, water, seeds,
and fertilizer effectively. The techniques have been applied on
166,000 ha of land.
</P>
<P>
Specialists from the United States, the Netherlands, and Canada
have introduced 10 modern techniques in Zhejiang by running
training courses or through joint operations. They have also
brought in more than 400 new varieties of wheat, fruits, and
flowers.
</P>
<P>
One Russian expert helped a chemical works in Wenzhou to make
potash fertilizer with a new technique he had invented, resulting
in both quality and profit increases.
</P>
<P>
According to the provincial government, Zhejiang will continue
to import foreign technology and investment in a planned way to
improve its economy in coming years. 
</P>
