<HEADLINE> 2.19 Billion US Dollars Invested In 6 Years In </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, February 27 (Xinhua) -- The investment climate
has just begun to gather some grounds in Tanzania, the local
paper "Business Express" reported today.
</P>
<P>
According to the paper, between September 1990 and December
1996, Tanzania attracted investments, both foreign and local,
worth 2.19 billion US Dollars from projects in 12 major sectors.
</P>
<P>
The investments include foreign projects, joint ventures, new
local projects and rehabilitation projects.
</P>
<P>
Out of the 12 sectors chalked out by the Investment Promotion
Center (IPC), the manufacturing sector seized a sizeable chunk of
more than one billion US Dollars for a total of 408 approved
projects by the IPC.
</P>
<P>
Other sectors which attracted major investments were tourism
with 270 million for 119 projects, agriculture and livestock with
about 91 million for 71 projects, natural resources about 108
million for 58 projects and the transport sector about 71 million
for 52 projects.
</P>
<P>
The least invested sectors were energy, computer and
telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
The financial sector has shown some hope for revival with 15
approved projects worth about 543 million US Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Sectors like petroleum and mining, construction and services
have also shown some improvement. 
</P>
