<HEADLINE> Mandela Meets Zairean Rebel Leader Kabila </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, February 27 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela has met visiting Zairean rebel leader
Laurent-Desire Kabila discussed the situation in eastern Zaire,
said a source here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters at his home in Johannesburg, where the
meeting was held on Wednesday night, Mandela said they also
discussed sensitive matters "where confidentiality is absolutely
essential".
</P>
<P>
Mandela returned from the Commonwealth African summit meeting
in Kasane, northern Botswana, on Wednesday to meet Kabila, who
arrived in the country secretly on Tuesday as part of continuing
multinational efforts to broker peace in eastern Zaire, said the
source.
</P>
<P>
Kabila said after the meeting that he was ready to have direct
negotiations with the Zairean government of President Mobutu Sese
Seko, but a ceasefire was a way off.
</P>
<P>
Kabila said he was glad to have received advice from Mandela
and hoped negotiations would start soon.
</P>
<P>
"We must maybe assume that peace can be found here with the
regime of Mobutu," he said.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Kabila also held talks with South African
officials and representatives of the United States, the United
Nations and the Organization of African Unity, said the source.
</P>
<P>
However, the rebel leader had not yet met Honore Ngbanda,
Mobutu's special envoy in South Africa for the multinatinal peace
talks, which started last week in Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
Tense situations are running high in eastern Zaire, where the
civil fighting between Kabila's rebel movement and Mobutu's
government force has caused a exodus of million of refugees in
the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
