<HEADLINE> China's Largest Offshore Oilfield in Bohai Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 27 (Xinhua) -- The Shengli Oilfield, China's
second largest oil field, has made a major breakthrough in oil
exploration in the Bohai Sea, off the eastern part of China, by
setting up the Chengdao Oilfield.
</P>
<P>
The new field, which has an annual output of 1.05 million tons,
is the largest offshore oilfield in the Bohai Bay, and has huge
production potential.
</P>
<P>
According to an official with the China National Petroleum Corp
(CNPC), the offshore oilfield was difficult to explore because of
its complicated geological structure. To develop the Chengdao
Field, Shengli has applied a large array of new technology that is
used for onshore purposes to offshore development, including a 3-D
seismic survey and oil reserve tracking technology.
</P>
<P>
The Bohai area now has an annual oil and gas output of 2.12
million tons and 367 million cubic meters respectively.
</P>
<P>
Oil officials say they expect greater progress this year in oil
and gas exploration in the Bohai area, with proven oil and gas
reserves forecast at 60 million tons and 10 billion cu m. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
