<HEADLINE> Kenyans Assured Enough Food to Arrest Famine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Tkhe Kenyan agriculture minister
has said that enough food had been imported to feed those people
living in drought-stricken areas in the country.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening session of the annual conference of
the Kenya National Farmers Union on Wednesday, Darius Mbela,
Minister for Agriculture, Livestock Development and Marketing,
stated that imported food was coming to help cope with the
food crisis.
</P>
<P>
Several cargo ships discharged about 70,000 tons of
grain last week and two additional vessels arrived on February 24
and 25 to unload a further 28,000 tons of maize and wheat.
</P>
<P>
The minister told the meeting that his government had decided
to spend about 110 million U.S. Dollars to import enough food to
arrest the looming famine caused by the current severe drought in
most parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
However, he pointed out, the imported food did not interfere
with domestic production, adding that duty and VAT payable on
food imports would be re-introduced as soon as the required
amounts were imported.
</P>
<P>
Mbela urged farmers throughout the country to increase
domestic grain production to cope with the rising population now
standing at some 28 million.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, farmers were advised to plant traditional food
crops such as cassava, potatoes and beans because they are
drought resistant. 
</P>
</TEXT>
