<HEADLINE> Xinhua International News Summary at 0800 GMT, February 27 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE -- The United Nations and the international civilian
mediator in Bosnia, Carl Bildt, Wednesday demanded the sacking and
arrest of the Bosnian Croat policemen accused of shooting at
Muslims in Mostar earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
Bildt also gave a deadline of midnight Wednesday for the
Bosnian Croat authorities to punish the troublemakers, according
to the U.N. spokesman in Banjaluka, Robert Wasserman.
</P>
<P>
Bildt's demands came following the release of a U.N. police
report that blamed the Bosnian Croat police for firing shots into
a group of several hundred Muslim pilgrims seeking to visit a
cemetery in the Croat-controlled part of Mostar, which has been
divided between Muslims and Croats since early 1993.
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- Mohammed Sahnoun, a U.N. envoy dealing with
the crisis in Central Africa, on Wednesday called for an immediate
halt to escalating fighting in Eastern Zaire between government
troops and ethnic Tutsi rebels.
</P>
<P>
"Ambassador Sahnoun is gravely concerned about the escalation
of fighting in Eastern Zaire, including the air bombings," said
U.N. spokesman Juan-Carlos Brandt.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that the fighting was worsening the plight of
the civilian population and of thousands of refugees, and impeding
the delivery of humanitarian assistance.
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- Secretary-General Kofi Annan on Wednesday
dismissed two senior officials of the Rwanda war crime tribunal
following a U.N. report that the court was riddled with
mismanagement and financial waste.
</P>
<P>
The report released two weeks ago by karl Paschke, U.N.
insector-general, detailed administrative mismangement,
unqualified staff and legal chaos.
</P>
<P>
"The Secretary-General decided that the continuation of two
officials of the tribunal in their posts would not be in the
interests of the United Nations and of the work of the tribunal in
a case involving human tragedy of incalculable proportion," U.N.
spokesman Juan-Carlos Brandt said.
</P>
<P>
NEW YORK -- Stocks on Wall Street fell sharply Wednesday along
with bonds, as more investors translating Federal Reserve chairman
Alan Greenspan's latest remarks as negative to the market.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industry average fell 55.03 to 6,983.18, having
recovered from a nearly 123-point tumble in the afternoon. It made
an instant response to another warning by Greenspan at the
Congress that the market's quick rise poses an inflationary risk.
</P>
<P>
Decliners outnumbered advancers by more than a 2-to-1 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with NYSE volume totaled 566.22
million shares up from 527.44 million in the previous session.
</P>
</TEXT>
