<HEADLINE> Investment Rises in Philippines' Southern Mindanao </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 27 (Xinhua) -- The investment injected into
the Philippines' Southern Mindanao last year surged to 1.028
billion U.S. dollars, an increase of 82 percent over the 566.5
million dollars in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Ariel Nengasca, information officer of the Department of Trade
and Industry in the region, said the investment, which exceeded
the department's 760 million dollar target, was mostly attributed
to domestic stakeholders.
</P>
<P>
The most invested area last year was the mining and mineral
section, edging out tourism facilities which was placed second,
the Philippine News Agency today quoted Nengasca as saying.
</P>
<P>
Of the total investment, firms registered with the department's
Board of Investment contributed 293.6 million dollars while small
and medium-sized enterprises accounted for 193 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Other investment sources included industrial centers, banks,
and firms registered with the country's Securities and Exchange
Commission, which invested a total of 541 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Nengasca said Davao Province attracted the most investments in
the region cornering some 411 million dollars, about 40 percent of
the total.  
</P>
