<HEADLINE> Iran May Expel Turkish Ambassador: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, February 27 (Xinhua) -- The Iranian government intends
to expel Turkish diplomats, including its ambassador, Iran's
official daily Iran reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Persian daily said that Turkish Ambassador to Tehran Osman
Koruturk and the consul general to Orumiyeh, capital of West
Azarbaijan province, may be expelled.
</P>
<P>
The move is reportedly in retaliation for the attitude of
Ankara toward Iranian Ambassador to Turkey Mohammad Reza Baqeri.
</P>
<P>
However, the daily said that the report has not yet been
confirmed by official sources.
</P>
<P>
Some sources said that the Iranian ambassador was asked to
leave Ankara because of his strong statement about Islam and
fundamentalism. This aroused anger from the Turkish authorities
and mass media. they said.
</P>
<P>
In fact, the sources said, Baqeri has returned from Ankara
and has been still in Tehran.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said that the relations between Iran and
Turkey would be turning cold again or getting worse if the two
countries expel ambassadors from the other side.
</P>
<P>
Last April Turkey and Iran had expelled four diplomats from
each side on charge of espionage activities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
