<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Life Expectancy Shortened in Sub-Sahara </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Life expectancy for the
1990-95 period in sub-Saharan countries was estimated at 46.7
years, a decrease of 3.9 years from the previous five years,
"Times of Zambia" reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted the Washington Line Newsletter as saying
that life expectancy figures for Rwanda fell from 46.7 to 22.6
years while Kenya dropped from 55.7 to 54.1 years. The figures
dropped in all east African countries.
</P>
<P>
Ethnic wars and the AIDS virus were cited as the main causes
of the decrease in the life expectancy.
</P>
<P>
In the area of health, experts found that poor nutrition,
water supply, sanitation and domestic hygiene were responsible
for 33 percent of diseases in sub-Saharan Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
