<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Imposes Stricter Controls on Explosives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Chinese police say they will
control production and use of explosives by small mines more
strictly with a nationwide safety study to be done during the
first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
The illegal production and sale of explosives will be harshly
dealt with, according to a recent circular issued by the Ministry
of Public Security, which is calling for tighter controls on
explosives for civilian use.
</P>
<P>
Unauthorized dynamite production will be stopped, and equipment
and materials used in the process, as well as explosives, will be
destroyed, the circular said.
</P>
<P>
The ministry admits that controls on explosives are quite
chaotic or even out of control in some places, mainly because
people ignore the importance of safety.
</P>
<P>
"Illegally-produced dynamite or that stolen from units that
have permits to keep explosives are sometimes used by criminals,
greatly endangering public safety," said the circular, which
called on local police departments to form special teams to
carefully check the production, storage, and sale of explosives
and those units that have explosives, especially small coal or
other mines and rock quarries.
</P>
<P>
The perils associated with the use of explosives must be
removed within a certain amount of time, and mines and producers
that do not meet the safety standards should be closed, the
circular said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
