<DOCNO> XIE19970227.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Banks Boosting Competition in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, February 27 (Xinhua) -- The arrival of foreign banks
and, especially, the recent decision by the Chinese central bank
to allow eight foreign banks to handle RMB yuan business have
further fueled the competition in Shanghai's banking market.
</P>
<P>
Some local experts hold that these foreign banks, normally with
higher credit ratings, have become more viable on the local
financial market after they were granted the right to deal in the
yuan.
</P>
<P>
The joining of these foreign banks in the competition has
opened more channels for acquiring credits for local clients, and
local Chinese banks are encountering bigger challenges, the
experts say.
</P>
<P>
According to official figures, by the end of 1996 Shanghai had
46 foreign banking institutions and 147 representative offices set
up by foreign banking institutions, with assets totaling 13.55
billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Last year foreign banks made up 30 percent of the city's total
international clearance and 15 percent of its foreign exchange
businesses.
</P>
<P>
In this largest metropolis in the country Chinese commercial
banks have remained the leading banking players in the local
financial market, but the growth of their loans and their market
share have declined steadily year by year, according to the
experts.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the state commercial banks have to issue a certain
amount of policy loans for the government, while they are still
trying to become commercialized through reforms. This has made it
difficult for Chinese state-owned banks to compete with foreign
banks, they say.
</P>
<P>
The experts explain that currently Chinese banks and their
foreign counterparts are competing to attract professional
persons, and more and more local banking professionals have been
lured to work in foreign banks.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, they say, these foreign banks will bring many new
banking services into the city, which will be more challenging to
local Chinese banks that are used to providing fewer service items
to local clients.
</P>
<P>
These experts believe that the arrival of foreign banks will
bolster the banking reform in Shanghai and it also means the
further opening-up of the country's banking sector to the outside
world.
</P>
<P>
The competition will draw more international banking giants to
Shanghai and boost the economic development of the metropolis,
they expect, which will further speed up the pace of the city
becoming an international center of economy, finance and trade.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
