<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Industry in Favor of Signing Infotech Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, February 27 (Xinhua) -- India's industry is largely
in favor of the country signing the information technology
agreement, but it seeks a longer phase-out period for tariffs on
infotech products than will be applied to developed countries.
</P>
<P>
These are the key findings of a Department of Electronics
study, which sought the opinion of most industry associations on
the issue.
</P>
<P>
India will be entitled to "initial negotiating rights" if it
signs the agreement by March 31 this year. If it comes on board
after the date, it will still be eligible to join the agreement
but will lose these rights.
</P>
<P>
The agreement seeks to completely eliminate tariffs on
approximately 200 infotech product categories. Certain dates have
been proposed by which the tariffs are to be phased out, with the
process beginning in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The proposal covers mainly computer hardware products,
semiconductors and integrated circuits, computer software,
telecommunications equipment and other information technology
products.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was proposed and carried forward by the
Organization of Economic Cooperation and Development countries at
the World Trade Organization Ministerial Meeting in Singapore in
December last year. With the United States and the European Union
finally settling their differences, almost 30 countries agreed to
sign the accord.
</P>
<P>
The agreement is to be on a most favored nation (MFN) basis.
The MFN clause would permit India to export its products at nil
duty to its signatories even if the country does not itself join
the agreement, industry sources said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
