<DOCNO> XIE19970227.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Opening Drive Helps Liaoning's Agricultural Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Northeast China's Liaoning
province, a major heavy industrial base, is enhancing agricultural
development by stepping up the opening up process.
</P>
<P>
The province previously suffered from poor agricultural
production, and grain and other farm product supplies were largely
brought in from other provinces.
</P>
<P>
But in the 1990s, the provincial government, seeing its
deficiencies, accelerated agricultural development by putting a
large amount of funding into farm projects. Various sources of
foreign funds have been used, and the province has used World Bank
loans of 86 million US dollars and set up 3,300 foreign-funded
firms involved in farming, with foreign funds of 2.2 billion US
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The province also held two large fairs to woo foreign
investment in agriculture last year and is planning on holding
another later this year, along with neigbouring Jilin and
Heilongjiang provinces and the Inner Mongolia autonomous region.
</P>
<P>
One vice-governor says that the province will list planting,
animal husbandry, aquiculture, and forestry and special local
products as priorities of opening up in the next few
years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
