<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's Experts Call Rail Budget Inflationary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Railway Minister Ram V.
Pawan's railway budget for 1997-98 presented to parliament
Wednesday has been described as inflationary by economic experts
and industrialists in the country.
</P>
<P>
The decision to increase freight charges by 12 percent over all
distances would increase production costs, which in turn would
raise the prices of bulk commodities, they said.
</P>
<P>
"The prices of products like cement and coal will rise and will
add to the prices of other commodities," economist D. H.
Paipanandikar said.
</P>
<P>
India's three apex chambers of industry have said that the hike
in fare and freight rates would lead to increased inflation.
</P>
<P>
President of the Associated Chambers of Commerce and Industry
H. L. Somany said that the hikes in fare and freight rates would
increase production costs and fuel inflation.
</P>
<P>
Sekhar Datta, president of the Confederation of Indian Industry
said that a major cause for worry was the fact that the freight
target had not been met. The target of freight loading in 1997-98,
an increase of 10.3 percent over 1996-97, is considered low
against a backdrop of 9.8 percent industrial growth. Roads were
carrying a disproportionately high percentage of freight traffic
(60 percent) and the figure would reach 65 percent by 2000.
</P>
<P>
President of the Federation of Indian Chambers of Commerce and
Industry A.S. Kasliwal said that the cumulative impact of the
freight hike would work out to 23.2 percent if the hike in July is
also taken into account.
</P>
<P>
The three apex chambers of industry also said that the burden
on the common man could have been reduced by involving the private
sector more effectively in the functioning of the railways.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
