<HEADLINE> Low-Interest Loans for Thailand's Textile Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Thai Deputy Prime Minister
Amnuay Virawan has approved an urgent proposal to grant 2 billion
baht (80 million US dollars) in low-interest loans to help revive
the troubled textile industry, according to an industry ministry
source.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Thailand's garment exports dropped by 21.7 percent
and fabrics by 5.8 percent from 1995. In 1996 garments and fabrics
were among the country's major export categories, ranking second
and 14th respectively.
</P>
<P>
The government expects the measure will help boost the
competitiveness of textile manufacturers by improving the
efficiency of their production processes.
</P>
<P>
To qualify for borrowing, applicants must display financial
stability and good export performances and that the new machinery
they wish to buy must be highly efficient and suitable.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Thailand, the Industrial Finance Corporation of
Thailand and the Export and Import Bank of Thailand will provide
the loans, at expected interest rates of 8 to 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
At present the interest rate for prime customers is 13-14
percent and more than 15 percent for general customers.
</P>
<P>
Suchart Chantaranakakaracha, vice president of the Thai Garment
Manufacturers' Association, said it was good news for the industry
as money was needed to obtain more efficient machinery to produce
value-added products.  
</P>
</TEXT>
