<HEADLINE> Donors Press Dhaka for Petrol, Fertilizer Price Hike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Donors put forth a series of
suggestions for Bangladesh, including lifting of government
control on petroleum, gas and fertilizer prices, in an interim
meeting that ended here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed by Finance Minister Shah Asm Kibria, who
presided over the meeting and briefed 30 donor representatives on
the economic policies of the government.
</P>
<P>
The finance minister said that the donors regarded the existing
prices of fuel oil, gas and fertilizer as unrealistic.
</P>
<P>
"In their view, an upward adjustment of prices was necessary in
order to avoid burden on the budget and pressure on balance of
payments and to allow market forces to operate without hindrance,"
said Kibria.
</P>
<P>
"We have noted the very strong concern expressed by the donors
that the low prices of oil, urea and gas result in a heavy loss of
public revenue. The suggestion will be placed before the
government for consideration," Kibria was quoted by the local
press.
</P>
<P>
The donors also expressed concern over the slow pace of
privatization, said Kibria, adding that the government would make
a "comprehensive statement" on privatization soon to achieve the
target of disinvestment program of the state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The interim meeting was significant as the donors would make
fresh aid commitment to Bangladesh after reviewing the country's
economic growth and reform progress, the finance minister added.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh, one of the most undeveloped countries, received a
commitment of 1.9 billion US dollars at the last aid club meeting
held in Paris last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
