<HEADLINE> Vietnam's Rural Roading Improved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam expanded, upgraded and
built 935 kilometers roads in rural and highland areas last year,
making 9,209 (93.8 percent) of Vietnam's communes now accessible
to roads.
</P>
<P>
The local press reported today that 1,567 billion Vietnamese
dong (about 142 million U.S. dollars) was spent on the work last
year, with 62 percent contributed by local people, who also gave
25.3 million working days.
</P>
<P>
The achievements in developing rural roads were attributed to
efforts made by local people and the effective use of government
investment.
</P>
<P>
The Transport and Communication Ministry has set a target of
expanding the road network to the remaining 607 communes, mainly
in highlands and remote areas inhabited by ethnic minorities and
in the Mekong river delta, by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The ministry also plans to allocate between 220 and 240 billion
dong (around 20 million U.S. dollars), contributed by
international organizations and foreign governments, to develop
communication networks in rural and highlands areas. 
</P>
