<HEADLINE> Parlatino to Meet in Costa Rica Next Month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, February 26 (Xinhua) -- Foreign debt, drug
trafficking and human rights are among the points to be discussed
when the Latin American parliament (Parlatino) meets here on March
13-15,
</P>
<P>
Rolando Gonzalez, who is an alternate secretary general of the
Parlatino, announced the session dates today.
</P>
<P>
Gonzalez described the meeting as the most important of those
held every year by the institution. It would step up condemnation
of the United States Helms-Burton law and stand side-by-side with
European parliamentarians, who requested the World Trade
Organization to set up a panel to investigate the globally
denounced legislation.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. legislation was imposed last year. It aims at
blockading Cuba by punishing foreign companies doing business with
the Caribbean island nation.
</P>
<P>
The agenda of the meeting will also include a proposal to
create a Latin American Commonwealth, and different initiatives to
deal with the problem of foreign debt and the treatment of illegal
aliens.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 100 legislators from 22 Latin American countries will
attend the gathering of the Parlatino, which was set up 30 years
ago in Lima, Peru to promote Latin American integration.
</P>
<P>
The committees that will meet are those on women, human rights,
agriculture, energy and mines, drug trafficking and foreign debt.
</P>
<P>
As for the United States' decision regarding the anti-drug
performances of Latin American countries, Gonzalez did not rule
out the possibility that the matter could be dealt with by the
Parlatino.
</P>
<P>
One of the fundamental principles of the Latin American
parliament was to respect the sovereignty of its members. In that
case, the U.S. involvement would infringe upon the sovereignties
of the Parlatino nations, Gopzalez said.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the creation of a Latin American Commonwealth,
Gonzalez, who is also deputy for the ruling National Liberation
Party (NLP) in Costa Rica, ruled out any intention of it becoming
a substitute for the Organization of American States (OAS).
</P>
<P>
Gonzalez said the Parlatino was taking steps to go to the
international court of The Hague in consultation over the legality
of an "excessive increase in interest rates" as it affected
foreign debt.
</P>
<P>
The Parlatino asked Pope John Paul II to speak out about the
rise in interest rates which were strangling a good number of the
economies in the region, Gonzalez noted.
</P>
<P>
"There are nations asphyxiated by this injustice," he said,
numerous acts of corruption had occurred in external debt
matters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
