<HEADLINE> UN Demands Arrest of Croat Policemen Over Mostar Shooting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, February 26 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations and the
international civilian mediator in Bosnia, Carl Bildt, today
demanded the sacking and arrest of the Bosnian Croat policemen
accused of shooting at Muslims in Mostar earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
Bildt also gave a deadline of midnight tonight for the Bosnian
Croat authorities to punish the troublemakers, according to the UN
spokesman in Banjaluka, Robert Wasserman.
</P>
<P>
Bildt's demands came following the release of a UN police
report that blamed the Bosnian Croat police for firing shots into
a group of several hundred Muslim pilgrims seeking to visit a
cemetery in the Croat-controlled part of Mostar, which has been
divided between Muslims and Croats since early 1993.
</P>
<P>
The February 10 shooting, one of the worst incidents of ethnic
violence since the 1995 Dayton peace accord, left one Muslim dead
and 22 injured.
</P>
<P>
The report, produced by a team of eight UN police officers and
released in Belgrade today, said that two Croat police officers
fired at the Muslim crowd and some 15 Croat police officers beat
them just before the shooting broke out.
</P>
<P>
Bildt's deputy, Michael Steiner, reportedly met last night with
leaders of Bosnia's Muslim-Croat Federation and asked them to
accept the UN police report on the Mostar incident.
</P>
<P>
The Bosnian Muslim leader Alija Izetbegovic has accepted the
report, but the Bosnian Croat leader Kresimir Zubak has rejected
it, saying that the UN should investigate the incident from all
sides.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Croat police in Mostar have sued 11
Muslim police officers in the town, accusing them of being
responsible for the shooting incident.
</P>
<P>
The Multinational Stabilization Force (SFOR) in Mostar has been
put on alert to deal with possible trouble. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
