<DOCNO> XIE19970227.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukraine's Health Care Situation Is Grim, Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, February 26 (Xinhua) -- Millions of Ukrainians are
chronically ill and the country's crumbling health care system is
unable to cope, local reports said.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine's Minister of Public Health Andre Serdyuk has painted a
grim picture of the health of this nation of 52 million people.
</P>
<P>
Six million Ukrainians, or nearly one in nine of the
population, suffer from cardio-vascular diseases, 800,000 have
cancer and tumor-related diseases, 760,000 have tuberculosis and
700,000 are alcoholics, he said recently.
</P>
<P>
Some 1.2 million people are mentally ill and 1.2 million are
disabled. The number of people suffering sexually-transmitted
diseases and AIDS is also rising rapidly.
</P>
<P>
He also warned that thyroid diseases among the victims of the
Chernobyl nuclear accident in 1986 are increasing and more and
more children are suffering from congenital diseases, indicating a
worrying change in the population's genetic coding.
</P>
<P>
The high rate of sickness and poor health care have led to 1.2
million extra deaths over the last six years and experts warn a
further 1.2 million people will die if the health care system
is not improved.
</P>
<P>
Nearly one in four Ukrainians were classed as aged, the highest
rate in Europe, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
But the public health care system is starved of funds as the
government undertakes painful economic reform to transform the
country from a centrally planned economy into a market economy.
</P>
<P>
The public health ministry has drafted a law on medical
insurance to improve the system and is trying to raise funds for
health care to supplement the state's annual medical subsidies
equivalent to 19 U.S. dollars per person.
</P>
<P>
The law will also require employers to insure their staff for
medical care, but that will be tough order for employers, most of
whom haven't even paid out salaries for six months.
</P>
<P>
Serdyuk said that only a healthy economy could secure a sound
health care system. But President Leonid Kuchma has said that it
would take 15-20 years for Ukraine to fully recover from the
current economic crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970227.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian House Passes Nuclear Power Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's House of
Representatives approved a draft bill on nuclear power at a
plenary session here Wednesday, but the government pledged not to
build a nuclear power plant in the near future.
</P>
<P>
State Minister of Research and Technology B.J. Habibie said at
the session that the government would have to go nuclear once
other energy sources failed to meet future needs.
</P>
<P>
"There are alternatives, like geothermal in Sumatra or
hydropower and natural gas. Going nuclear will be the government's
last step," he said.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary studies costing 22 billion rupiah (9.5 million US
dollars), including feasibility research, on a nuclear power plant
have been underway near the dormant volcano Mt. Muria in Jepara,
Central Java, for the past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
However, Habibie said that the government had yet to decide
whether to go ahead with the planned nuclear plant, which is
expected to produce 7,200 megawatts of electricity.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's plenary meeting was marked by a demonstration of
protesters outside who called themselves the anti-nuclear society.
The group's spokesperson Agus Mahesa said the government must
consider the storage of nuclear waste and the maintenance of the
nuclear project. 
</P>
</TEXT>
