<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Challenges Argentina on Leather Restrictions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, February 26 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission (EC)
is challenging Argentina for severely limiting the export of cow
hides to the European Union, thereby choking off an essential
supply of raw material for European producers of high-quality
finished leather goods.
</P>
<P>
Following a complaint from the European tanning industry under
the Trade Barriers Regulation, the EC has decided to make an
in-depth analysis of a number of Argentinian practices, it was
learned here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The European tanning industry alleges that Argentina operates a
tacit export ban on raw cow hides by means of a 15 percent export
tax, as well as through the influence of the country's tanning
representatives in the customs control system.
</P>
<P>
This had enabled Argentina's leather industry to undercut its
European competitors on world markets, the Commission said.
</P>
<P>
The European tanning industry also claims that Argentina
applies discriminatory taxes to imports of finished leather
products into Argentina.
</P>
<P>
The EC's action is part of its new Market Access Strategy,
which aims at a more effective targeting of trade barriers that
hinder European exports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
