<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar to Boost Paddy Output in 1997-98 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar has taken measures to
boost cultivation and production of paddy, which is the staple
crop of the country, beginning from 1997-98, the second fiscal
year of the present five year plan (1996-1997 to 2000-2001).
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with officials of the major paddy-cultivating
areas in different states and divisions here on Wednesday, Myanmar
Minister for Agriculture and Irrigation Myint Aung said that of
the 10.6 million acres (4.29 million hectares) which receive
suitable amounts of water and rain in the country, 6 million acres
(2.43 million hectares) have been selected for cultivation with an
average target of 75 baskets per acre (3.86 tons per hectare),
official daily The New Light of Myanmar reported today.
</P>
<P>
Land preparation is to be made on the remaining areas according
to their geographical and soil conditions, and measures are to be
taken for an average yield of 50 baskets per acre (2.58 tons per
hectare), he urged.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar's agriculture, which is the mainstay of the country's
economy, accounts for about 38 percent of the total GDP and about
40 percent of foreign exchange earnings.
</P>
<P>
According to the official statistics, Myanmar's paddy output in
the last 1995-96 fiscal year was recorded at 19 million tons,
while its rice export was at 353,100 tons. The target for the
1996-97 fiscal year is to produce 20 million tons of paddy and
export 1 million tons of rice.
</P>
<P>
The annual growth rate of Myanmar's agriculture in the last
four fiscal years from 1992-93 to 1995-96 stood at 8.8 percent and
is targeted at 5.4 per cent in the next five fiscal years from
1996-97 to 2000-2001.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
