<DOCNO> XIE19970227.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swiss Government Formally Creates Fund for Holocaust Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, February 26 (Xinhua) -- Swiss Foreign Minister Flavio
Cotti announced today that the Swiss government has formally set
up a special fund for Nazi Holocaust victims.
</P>
<P>
The special fund, which goes into operation on March 1, is
intended "to give support to persons in need who were persecuted
for racial, religious, political, or other reasons, including
those who in any other way were victims of the Holocaust, as well
as to assist their descendants in need."
</P>
<P>
Cotti said, "All institutions and organizations dedicated to
the objectives of the special fund are entitled to submit
requests."
</P>
<P>
The Swiss Foreign Minister said that the government "is
assuming its role as leader" in setting up a structure to assure
that urgent humanitarian assistance efforts will be able to be
carried out during the coming months.
</P>
<P>
The fund's foundation was first announced on February 12 and
will be administered by a government-appointed council.
The fund will initially consist of the 100 million francs (about
71 million U.S. dollars) set aside on February 5 by the three
biggest Swiss banks, and further infusions from other branches of
the economy.
</P>
<P>
The fund executive will be made up of four Swiss citizens
including the country's president and three others from the World
Jewish Restitution Organization (WJRO). Half of the 18-member
fund council will be chosen on the recommendation of the
WJRO. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
