<HEADLINE> Ukraine, Italy Look at Smaller Businesses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, February 26 (Xinhua) -- Ukraine and Italy will improve
cooperation in the establishment of small- and medium-sized
businesses, which is essential for bilateral relations, the
visiting Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi said here today.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting with his Ukrainian counterpart, Pavel Lazarenko,
Prodi also said that Italy is interested in importing raw
materials from Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
Heading a delegation of 60 businessmen, Prodi arrived in Kiev
on Tuesday for a two-day visit.
</P>
<P>
There are now 172 Italian companies and 140 Italian-Ukrainian
joint ventures in this former Soviet republic, most of which are
food and manufacturing enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Prodi said Italy hopes to invest in Ukraine's agriculture,
which is a vital part of the Ukrainian economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral trade reached 663 million dollars in 1996, accounting
for nine percent of Ukraine's trade with European countries.
</P>
<P>
Italian investment in Ukraine totaled 25.9 million dollars late
last year. Lazarenko said he hopes that Italian investment would
also go into Ukraine's energy and transportation sectors.
</P>
<P>
However, there was a major problem. Lazarenko wished that
Ukraine's debts to Italy could be reduced or even written off
before 2004. He did not release figure of the debts.
</P>
<P>
Lazarenko said he expects the Italian government to give
Ukraine loans of 100 billion Liras (about 88.5 million
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Prodi did not comment on the loans at a later press conference.
</P>
<P>
He said Italy supports Ukraine's integration with the European
Union and the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
The Italian prime minister suggested a transport corridor be
built to link Italy's Trieste and Kiev through Slovenia and
Hungary. 
</P>
</TEXT>
