<DOCNO> XIE19970227.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNCTAD: Asia's Investment in Europe Increases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Foreign direct investment (FDI)
flows from Asia into Europe soared from an average 100 million
U.S. dollars during 1989-1991 to an average 860 million dollars
during 1992-1994, a report released here today by the United
Nations Conference on Trade and Development (UNCTAD) said.
</P>
<P>
In the report entitled "Sharing Asia's Dynamism: Asian Direct
Investment in the European Union (EU)", UNCTAD said that many
firms from Asia's newly industrializing economies (NIEs), such as
Hong Kong, South Korea, Singapore and Taiwan, increasingly find a
direct presence in the EU necessary to serve this large, wealthy
market.
</P>
<P>
Others are seeking access to advanced technology and skills,
research and development programs, the report said.
</P>
<P>
However, Asian FDI in the EU accounted for only five percent of
the total FDI from the region in 1995, reflecting the fact that
"Asian firms are just at the beginning of their entry into
Europe", the report pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The report noted that the United Kingdom is the most popular
destination for Asian NIEs' investment, which accounts for 40
percent of the FDI. Germany and the Netherlands followed with 30
percent and 20 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
More recently, Asian transnational corporations have began
investing in Central and Eastern Europe, where they find a
low-cost production base and a good platform for relatively
unrestricted entry into the EU's internal market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970227.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Newspaper Highlights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 27 (Xinhua) -- All major Beijing-based
newspapers today devote space to reports of people mourning the
death of Deng Xiaoping and to reports on studying the funeral
speech of Party General Secretary Jiang Zemin by leading officials
and people of all ethnic groups in China.
</P>
<P>
"People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- The Funeral Committee for Deng Xiaoping issued its third
announcement, expressing gratitude to the heads of state and
government, legislatures, government departments, political
parties, organizations and prominent figures from various circles
in many countries, heads of international organizations,
diplomatic envoys to China, foreign friends in China, overseas
Chinese, and compatriots in Hong Kong, Macao and Taiwan who sent
telegrams and letters of condolence or participated in memorial
services to express their grief and profound sympathy for Deng's
death.
</P>
<P>
-- Delegates to the National People's Congress and members of
the National Committee of the Chinese People's Political
Consultative Conference (CPPCC) who have come to Beijing for the
national conference honored the memory of Deng and pledged to live
up to the trust and expectations of the people and to turn grief
into strength and do a good job in state affairs.
</P>
<P>
-- Under the banner headline: "Beloved Comrade Deng Xiaoping
will forever live in our hearts," the paper devotes an entire page
to people in various parts of China recalling Deng's achievements
and contributions to the Chinese revolution and socialist
construction.
</P>
<P>
-- The Fifth Session of the National Committee of the Eighth
Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference will open in
Beijing this afternoon. A front page editorial hails its opening
and cites Deng's great contribution to united front work.
</P>
<P>
"Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- A front page report says that leading officials and the
masses of people in China are conscientiously studying the funeral
speech delivered by Jiang Zemin, general secretary of the Central
Committee of the Communist Party of China, and have vowed to turn
grief into strength, carry out Deng's behest and accomplish a
great cause under the leadership of the Party Central Committee
with comrade Jiang Zemin at the core. The report describes scenes
of people in Guizhou, Guangxi, Liaoning, Jiangsu and Hebei
provinces, Inner Mongolia and Shanghai watching the live broadcast
of the memorial meeting for Deng in the Great Hall of People in
Beijing on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
-- the General Political Department of the PLA released a
circular yesterday that calls for all troops and armed police to
study President Jiang Zemin's memorial speech for Deng Xiaoping.
</P>
<P>
-- Departments under the CPC Central Committee and the central
government have held various activities to commemorate Deng
following the funeral meeting.
</P>
<P>
-- A seminar marking the 50th anniversary of the Taiwan
"February 28 Uprising" was held in Beijing yesterday. Li Ruihuan,
member of the Standing Committee of the Political Bureau of the
CPC Central Committee and chairman of the CPPCC, attended.
</P>
<P>
"China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- More heads of state and governments worldwide visited
Chinese embassies or sent messages of condolence for Deng's death.
</P>
<P>
-- The paper carries the full text of a People's Daily
editorial which salutes Deng's legacy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
