<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fossils of Prehistoric Mammal Found in Argentina </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, February 26 (Xinhua) -- Fossils of a glyptodon, a
mammal that lived 10 million years ago, were found in northern
Argentina, archaeologist said today.
</P>
<P>
The discovery was made by researchers from Miguel Lilio
Institute while they were working on geological formations in
Santa Maria in the northern province of Catamarca.
</P>
<P>
The fossilized remains of the mammal are very similar to those
of a small mule, or a quirquincho (a kind of armadillo), but
slightly bigger.
</P>
<P>
The researchers said that the skeleton was very well preserved
and was of great scientific value since this was the first fossil
of an mammal to be found in Santa Maria. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970227.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panama to Fine Unsafe Ship Owners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, February 26 (Xinhua) -- Panama receives about 45
million dollars a year for the registration of ships and will fine
any ship flying a Panamanian flag that fails to comply with the
minimum safety requirements.
</P>
<P>
There are more than 13,000 of ships flying Panamanian flags and
they have a gross weight of 100 million tons, said Abraham Sofer,
director of consular services and ships for the Finance and
Treasury Ministry.
</P>
<P>
At a seminar on maritime safety being held in Panama City,
Sofer said Panama was prepared to improve safety on ships flying
the Panamanian flag and to broaden its relations with the
International Maritime Organization as well.
</P>
<P>
A maritime safty code would become effective this July.
</P>
<P>
More than 70 people from some 28 countries are taking part in
the seminar, the first of its kind. 
</P>
</TEXT>
