<DOCNO> XIE19970227.0256 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> All Habitats for Giant Pandas to Be Put Under State Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 27 (Xinhua) -- All the existing wild habitats
for giant pandas in China will be put under state protection in
the next few years, according to a plan to be carried out soon.
</P>
<P>
Wang Zhibao, Vice-Minister of Forestry, said in an interview
with Xinhua News Agency that his ministry is now planning to
increase the current reserves for giant pandas from 14 to 28, in a
move to cover all the main habitats for giant pandas.
</P>
<P>
In order to do so, he said, a number of lumber mills that may
cause damage to the ecosystems of the habitats for the giant panda
will be closed.
</P>
<P>
He said that preliminary work on the project has begun, with 25
million yuan (three million US dollars) in special funding
allocated for the relocation and replacement of a lumber mill in
northwest China's Shaanxi Province, one of the main habitats for
giant pandas.
</P>
<P>
According to the Vice-Minister, however, the lack of funds is
blocking the smooth implementation of the plan.
</P>
<P>
"Together with other related departments, the ministry will
work to channel more funds and seek wide international
cooperation," Wang said.
</P>
<P>
In 1962, China put the giant panda, a world famous rare animal
that only exists in the country, under the top state
protection. Only about 1,000 giant pandas now live in China.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that since 1983, as many as 161 giant pandas
that suffered from hunger or disease have received medical
attention and recovered, and 120 were saved from near death.
</P>
<P>
Since 1991, 16 giant pandas have been born as a result of
artificial insemination carried out by the research center for
giant pandas under the Ministry of Forestry, and 11 survived,
according to Wang. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
