<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cape Town Apologises to Rome </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, February 26 (Xinhua) -- A Cape Town committee backing the
South African city's bid to host the 2004 Olympics has apologised
to Rome's committee for suggestions that it was behind a campaign
to hurt Cape Town's chance, the Italian National Olympic Committee
(INOC) said here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Chris Ball, president of the committee promoting Cape Town's
bid, has personally apologised to the INOC president Mario
Pescante.
</P>
<P>
Ball's letter contained an "unconditional" apology but stressed
that his statements on an alleged knocking campaign had been
"misunderstood."
</P>
<P>
Ball was said to have voiced the hope that good relations
between all bidders for the Games could be maintained.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Ball was reported to have charged that the Rome 2004
committee was behind reports in the Italian media highlighting the
alleged crime problems in Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
Media reports followed the release of an International Olympic
Committee (IOC) report assessing the eleven candidate cities for
the 2004 Games.
</P>
<P>
In that report, Rome and Athens came top but Cape Twon was also
rated among the front-runners along with Buenos Aires, with
Stockholm a shade behind.
</P>
<P>
Rome and Athens shared traffic problems, while Buenos Aires
might have funding problems, and Stockholm faced local
indifference to the Games, the report said. Cape Town's crime
problem was cited, as was Rio's.
</P>
<P>
In addition to Rome and Cape Town, the candidate cities are
Istanbul, Stockholm, Seville, Lille, San Juan, Rio De Janeiro,
Buesnos Aires, Athens, and St. Peterburg.
</P>
<P>
The IOC panel evaluating the candidates is expected to name
five finalists on March 7 and the winner will be announced on
September 7. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
