<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Trying to Save Cultural Relics At Dam Project Site </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scholars are trying
to minimize the damage to cultural relics from the Three Gorges
Area where China is building its largest water conservation
project.
</P>
<P>
Large-scale development has revealed some 830 underground
historical sites and 450 ancient buildings and stone carvings in
the area, where human activities can be traced back to at least
30,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
A cultural relics conservation plan was completed last summer,
with suggestions for excavating major historical sites, move
important buildings and carvings, and protecting some special
monuments at the site.
</P>
<P>
A dam will be set up, as part of this, to protect Shibaozai, a
wooden structure building built along a mountainside in the Ming
Dynasty (1368-1644), while a temple from the Qing Dynasty
(1644-1911) and two groups of residential buildings will be moved
in their entirety, and an underwater museum estimated to cost 100
million yuan will be built to protect carvings in Baiheliang,
which was done during a period of more than 1,000.
</P>
<P>
Yu Weichao, curator of the prestigious National Museum of
Chinese History, who is in charge of the conservation of cultural
relics in the Three Gorges Area, said that the water conservation
project ironically promoted the excavation and conservation of
cultural relics in the area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
