<DOCNO> XIE19970227.0264 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East China Outlines Agricultural Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Shandong, one of China's leading
grain producers, will increase efforts to develop its agriculture
this year, with the aim of repeating the record grain harvest last
year.
</P>
<P>
The province harvested 43.3 billion kg of grain in 1996, an all
time high, despite a serious drought in the spring and big floods
in the summer.
</P>
<P>
It plans to increase the annual grain output to 43.5 billion kg
and produce 4.4 billion kg of cotton and 32 billion kg of peanuts
this year. To do that, the local government plans to build 10
large and medium-sized reservoirs with a total additional water
storage capacity of 200 million cubic meters,
</P>
<P>
It will also speed up reclamation and soil improvement on the
Huaihe-Huanghe-Haihe plain, the Yellow River Delta, and at
Dongping and Nansi lakes.
</P>
<P>
Organizations that integrate agriculture with industry and
trade will be set up to help farmers develop a market-oriented
sense and pillar industries for rural areas.
</P>
<P>
With a "developing agriculture through science and education"
strategy, all rural areas are urged to develop fine strains, build
more experimental wheat, maize, cotton and vegetable plots, boost
high-yield, high-quality, and high-efficiency agriculture, and
raise the cultural level of farmers by running training
courses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
