<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Cultural Relics Discovered in South China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Guangzhou, one of the most
economically developed cities in China, discovered some 750
cultural relics last year at 54 ancient tombs and a kiln site.
</P>
<P>
Major finds in 1996 included building remains from the Han
Dynasty (206 BC-220 AD), a dam site from the Song Dynasty
(960-1279), a neolithic site in an economic development zone, and
a group of tombs from the Western Han Dynasty (206 BC-24 AD).
</P>
<P>
One of China's historical cities, Guangzhou itself has 16
historical monuments and sites under state protection, including
the imperial palace site of the Nanyue Kingdom from some 2,000
years ago.
</P>
<P>
That site dates from the same period as the Changle and Weiyang
imperial palaces of the Western Han Dynasty in Xi'an, but has
yielded even more cultural relics than those.
</P>
<P>
The discovery of the Nanyue palaces was among the Top Ten
Chinese Archaeological Finds of 1995.
</P>
<P>
Guangzhou has spent some 100 million yuan in building an art
museum, and has decided to allocate a total of 11 million yuan for
cultural relics collection and conservation each year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
