<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Dismisses Top Officials in UN Rwanda Tribunal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, February 26 (Xinhua) -- Secretary-General Kofi
Annan on Wednesday dismissed two senior officials of the Rwanda
war crime tribunal following a U.N. report that the court was
riddled with mismanagement and financial waste.
</P>
<P>
The report released two weeks ago by karl Paschke, U.N.
insector-general, detailed administrative mismangement,
unqualified staff and legal chaos.
</P>
<P>
"The Secretary-General decided that the continuation of two
officials of the tribunal in their posts would not be in the
interests of the United Nations and of the work of the tribunal in
a case involving human tragedy of incalculable proportion," U.N.
spokesman Juan-Carlos Brandt said.
</P>
<P>
He said Annan had accepted in the "best interests of the United
Nations and the tribunal" the resignation of the deputy
prosecutor, Honoure Rakotomanana of Madagascar, and the court's
register Andonico Adede of Kenya, who in effect served as chief
administrator.
</P>
<P>
Brandt told reporters that Adede will be replaced by Agwu Ukiwe
Okali of Nigeria, a graduate of the London School of Economics and
Harvard Law School, who is currently serving in the U.N. Habitat
Office in Nairobi. A new prosecutor has not yet been named, he
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
