<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Europeans Visit Each Other More: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, February 26 (Xinhua) -- More and more Europeans are
visiting each other's countries as tourists, says a report
published here today.
</P>
<P>
Nights spent by non-residents in EU member states in all types
of registered tourist accommodation rose by 4.3 percent in the
previous two years -- 1995 and 1996 -- to stand at over 720
million, according to Eurostat, the EU's statistical office.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, nights spent by non-residents represented 39 percent
of the total "tourist nights" in the EU. "This confirms the
growing importance of international tourist flows, mainly between
European countries," says the report.
</P>
<P>
The report also shows nights spent by people in their own
country increased by 1.9 percent in 1995 and 1996 to an estimated
nearly 1,099 million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
