<HEADLINE> UN Envoy Calls for Halt to Fighting in Eastern Zaire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, February 26 (Xinhua) -- Mohammed Sahnoun, a
U.N. envoy dealing with the crisis in Central Africa, on Wednesday
called for an immediate halt to escalating fighting in Eastern
Zaire between government troops and ethnic Tutsi rebels.
</P>
<P>
"Ambassador Sahnoun is gravely concerned about the escalation
of fighting in Eastern Zaire, including the air bombings," said
U.N. spokesman Juan-Carlos Brandt at today's routine noon
briefing.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that the fighting was worsening the plight of
the civilian population and of thousands of refugees, and impeding
the delivery of humanitarian assistance.
</P>
<P>
"The large dispersion into inhospitable terrain of the
inhabitants of Eastern Zaire fleeing the fighting and the reported
discovery of mass graves benefit no one and discredit all
protagonists, no matter how legitimate their cause might be," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"Ambassador Sahnoun calls, once again, on all the parties to
abide by Security Council resolution 1097 and cease hostilities
immediately," he said. In resolution 1097, the Security Council
endorsed a five-point peace plan for the region culminating in an
international conference.
</P>
<P>
A halt to the fighting would enable the international community
to "establish the facts and consider the practical modalities for
the withdrawal of all foreign forces, including mercenaries,"
Brandt said.
</P>
<P>
It would also promote the establishment of a durable peace
through dialogue, the electoral process and the proposed
international conference, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
