<HEADLINE> Sultan Says No Rush for Probe into Dhahran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 26 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabia would not rush
to any conclusion of the investigation into the Last year's June
25 truck bombing in Dhahran air base, which killed 19 U.S.
servicemen, even though some progress has been made, Saudi Arabian
Deputy Prime Minister Prince Sultan said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We have not finished the investigation. We are not pointing
fingers yet at anybody," Prince Sultan told reporters during a
visit to the Pentagon when asked about the probe into the bomb
attack. "We are trying to make sure justice is seen to be done and
therefore we don't want to rush the investigation unnecessarily.
But there is progress."
</P>
<P>
Prince Sultan's comments came as he was greeted by Defense
Secretary William Cohen for talks midway through a five-day visit
to Washington in a bid to patch a crack in relations between the
two countries, caused by U.S. alleged lace of cooperations in the
investigation into the truck bombing.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration has complained that Saudi Arabia was
not sharing enough information with the FBI in its probe of the
blast, and U.S. FBI investigators in Saudi Arabia felt frustrated
in making any advance in finding out who was responsible for the
Dhahran blast.
</P>
<P>
Prince Sultan, however, said: "Our cooperation with our friends
is going in an excellent way and as soon as all the investigation
is complete we plan to reveal all the details."
</P>
<P>
Prince Sultan met President Bill Clinton on Tuesday and will
hold talks with Secretary of State Madeleine Albright on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He and a delegation that includes the Saudi foreign, oil and
trade ministers will stay until Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
