<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., Chilean Presidents Stress Hemispheric Free </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 26 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
and visiting Chilean President Eduardo Frei met in the White House
today and they stressed their desire to expand free trade in the
hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
The United States "cannot sit on the sidelines" while other
nations increase trade with Latin America, Clinton said at a joint
news conference with the Chilean president after their meeting.
</P>
<P>
"Our administration remains committed to concluding a
comprehensive free trade agreement with Chile," Clinton said,
adding that he wants to get so-called "fast track" trade
negotiation authority from Congress to conclude new trade
agreements that "open markets to America's products and that
advance our values."
</P>
<P>
President Frei told Clinton that trade within the Americas
should proceed "as if there were no frontiers."
</P>
<P>
Frei was here for a four-day visit in a task to bolster his
case for a reconstructed North American Free Trade Agreement
(NAFTA) that would include Chile.
</P>
<P>
Chile was invited to join the NAFTA, which links the United
States, Canada and Mexico, at the first Summit of the Americas in
Miami in December 1994.
</P>
<P>
Chile has concluded agreements with Canada and Mexico and other
Latin American countries and is negotiating a deal with the
European Union. But the lack of fast track authority has delayed
negotiations with the United States.
</P>
<P>
"At the crossroads of trade among the world's most dynamic
economies, Chile can be a cornerstone of the vibrant free-trade
area we are working to build in our hemisphere," Clinton said.
"The United States simply cannot sit on the sidelines while others
share in the fruits of Latin America's remarkable growth."
</P>
<P>
Clinton said unless Congress quickly renews his authority to
expand NAFTA, the United States risks losing to European and Asian
competitors already moving into America's economic back yard.
</P>
<P>
The president said he will send Agriculture Secretary Dan
Glickman to Chile to begin consultations on promoting trade in the
region. He also said the United States and Chile would begin
negotiating an aviation agreement.
</P>
<P>
Frei is to address a joint session of Congress on Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
