<HEADLINE> U.S. Reaffirms Opposition to WTO's Investigation on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 26 (Xinhua) -- The United States today
reaffirmed its opposition to the investigation of the World Trade
Organization (WTO) on a U.S.-European Union dispute over trading
with Cuba.
</P>
<P>
"This is not a foreign trade dispute between the United States
and the European Union; it's a foreign policy difference," U.S.
State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns told reporters.
</P>
<P>
WTO appointed three trade experts last week to set up a panel
to investigate the U.S.-EU dispute over the U.S. Helms-Burton law,
which is aimed at blocking Cuba.
</P>
<P>
The law, according to which, foreign companies will be punished
for trading with Cuba, was strongly criticized worldwide. EU
insists that it violates WTO's principles and submitted the case
to the organization.
</P>
<P>
The investigative panel was set up on February 20 after the
U.S. and EU failed to reach a settlement.
</P>
<P>
"The United States will not let the WTO adjudicate this," Burns
said. "It's not a trade problem...Helms-Burton is the law of the
land and we're going to implement it," Burns stressed.
</P>
<P>
However, the spokesman noted that both sides are still
negotiating a bilateral agreement on the row."We don't have an
agreement yet, but we have, I think, a common interest in reaching
one," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
