<HEADLINE> Stocks on Wall Street Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, February 26 (Xinhua) -- Stocks on Wall Street fell
sharply today along with bonds, as more investors translating
Federal Reserve chairman Alan Greenspan's latest remarks as
negative to the market.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industry average fell 55.03 to 6,983.18, having
recovered from a nearly 123-point tumble in the afternoon. It made
an instant response to another warning by Greenspan at the
Congress that the market's quick rise poses an inflationary risk.
</P>
<P>
Decliners outnumbered advancers by more than a 2-to-1 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with NYSE volume totaled 566.22
million shares up from 527.44 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list fell 6.43 to 805.67, and
the NYSE's composite index fell 3.39 to 422.14.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index fell 7.14 to 1,340.55, and the
American Stock Exchange composite index fell 2.68 to 597.31.
</P>
<P>
Greenspan refused to rule out the possibility of an interest
rate hike by the U.S. central bank to slow down the economy to
ease inflationary pressures, which he said could be exacerbated by
the continuing run-up in stock prices.
</P>
<P>
Bond prices fell immediately after Greenspan's remarks, pushing
the yield on the 30-year Treasury as high as 6.80 percent, up from
6.66 percent late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Dow component McDonald's was one of the big losers.
</P>
<P>
Dell Computer, which reported sharply higher earnings Tuesday
night, rose as the most active Nasdaq Stock Market issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
