<HEADLINE> U.S. Criticizes Israel for Building Housing in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 26 (Xinhua) -- The United States on
Wednesday criticized Israel's decision to build new Jewish housing
in Arab East Jerusalem, saying such a move would not be conducive
to building trust in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. remarks came shortly after Israel approved the
construction of 6,500 homes in Arab East Jerusalem despite strong
Palestinians' opposition. The home will go up at a tree-covered
hill taken by Israel in the 1967 Middle East war.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu defended the project
as a move by Israel to alleviate a shortage of housing for Arabs
and Jews in the city. But the Palestinians see it as an attempt to
cement Israel's hold over all of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
White House Spokesman David Johnson said: "The decision taken
today further complicates an already complicated situation."
</P>
<P>
Johnson said a deal on Hebron for Israeli troops to pull out of
the West Bank city had create an atmosphere in which to build
confidence and trust between the Israelis and Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
But the decision was not "the type of actions we would believe
that would help build that," he said. 
</P>
