<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Population Hits 109 Million: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 26 (Xinhua) -- The population of Nigeria,
Africa's most populous country, hit 109.04 million in 1995, the
official News Agency of Nigeria reported today.
</P>
<P>
It said the figure comes from the 1996 edition of the "The
Progress of Nigerian Children", a bulletin jointly published by
the Federal Office of Statistics (FOS) of Nigeria and the United
Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF).
</P>
<P>
The figure is 2.8 percent up from the 1994 figure of 106.33
million, the bulletin said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, the United Nations put the population of
Nigeria at 115 million by the end of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The joint publication of the FOS and UNICEF said Nigeria's
Gross National Products per capita declined 10 percent from 310
U.S. Dollars in 1993 to 280 U.S. Dollars in 1994.
</P>
<P>
It noted that the average monthly household expenditure in
1992/93 stood at 1,150 Naira (about 14 U.S. Dollars), of which 76
percent were spent on food alone.
</P>
<P>
An average household virtually spent all their income every
month, with only eight percent left for savings, the bulletin
said.
</P>
<P>
In the same period, the real income for Nigerian families
actually declined due to continued rise in prices, it noted.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, the country's inflation stood at 73 percent, 16
percent up from that of 1994.
</P>
<P>
And nearly 16 percent of Nigeria's urban youths between the
age of 15 of 24 were out of work in 1995. The figure was 4.9
percent for rural youths and 6.7 percent for the national
average, the bulletin added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
