<HEADLINE> Hundreds in Germany Mourn Over Deng's Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, February 26 (Xinhua) -- About 500 people from all walks
of life in Germany have been to the Chinese embassy here to pay
their respects to Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping who died in Beijing
last Wednesday at the age of 93.
</P>
<P>
Chief of Protocol of the German Foreign Ministry Von der
Planitz, representing German President Roman Herzog, Chancellor
Helmut Kohl and Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel, went to the
mourning hall at the embassy Monday to express deep sorrow over
Deng's death.
</P>
<P>
Among the mourners over the past few days were also former
German Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher, Governor of the
Rheinland-Pfalz state Kurt Beck and Hamburg Mayor Henning
Voscherau.
</P>
<P>
Voscherau told Chinese embassy staffers that Deng was "a great
man who had changed China and the world."
</P>
<P>
The Chinese embassy in Bonn has also received a number of
condolence telegrams and letters from German prominent figures
from various circles in recent days. They all spoke highly of
Deng's historic contribution to China's construction, and in
particular to the opening-up and reform cause.
</P>
<P>
Describing Deng as "a great thinker both of China and of the
world," one telegram said, "His passing away is not only a loss to
china, but also a loss to the whole world."
</P>
<P>
A number of overseas Chinese and Chinese students from
different parts of Germany also came to Bonn to express their
repects and condolences to the late Chinese leader.
</P>
<P>
President of the All-German Federation of Overseas Chinese
Peng Weibang told Xinhua that Deng Xiaoping was not only a great
man of China, but also a historical great man recognized by the
whole world. 
</P>
