<HEADLINE> PNA Condemns Israel for Jewish Settlement Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, February 26 (Xinhua) -- The permanent delegate of the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) to the Arab League (AL) today
denounced the Israeli government's plans for new Jewish
settlements in East Jerusalem and other Palestinian lands.
</P>
<P>
Mohamed Sobeih, who is also a senior PNA official, said these
plans constitute a blow to the peace process and drive the area to
extremism and violence.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian official called on the U.S. to adopt a decisive
stance as regards the settlement expansion "crime" committed by
Israel in East Jerusalem before "it is too late."
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu said Wednesday that
his government planned to build 2,000 apartments for Jews in Har
Homa area, located in East Jerusalem, which Israel captured in the
1967 Middle East War.
</P>
<P>
The project was included in a 43-million-U.S.-dollar
development plan approved by the Israeli cabinet on January 26 to
strengthen Israel's hold on East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Sobeih said that Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat will call a
meeting Thursday with all Palestinian factions to discuss the
issue of Jewish settlement and Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Sobeih said that the AL Council has held an emergency meeting
at the delegates' level regarding the Israeli settlement plans and
it is still open.
</P>
<P>
The AL, based on Cairo, is coordinating efforts in this respect
with the Arab, non-aligned and African groups at the U.N. Security
Council, he added.
</P>
<P>
AL Secretary General Esmat Abdul Meguid is conducting
intensified contacts with the permanent members of the
U.N. Security Council and Arab heads of state in this regard, he
said.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Netanyahu phoned Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak this afternoon on the establishment of the new
settlements in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak warned that Israel should avoid any act that may damage
the peace process and intensify tensions.
</P>
<P>
The Jewish state says all of Jerusalem is its eternal and
undivided capital. But the Palestinians hope to make East
Jerusalem, which contains Judaism's holiest site and Islam's third
holiest shrine, capital of a Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's Crown Prince Hassan decided Tuesday to postpone a
visit to the Jewish state in reaction to the Israeli decision. He
put off a visit last fall after the opening of a tunnel in East
Jerusalem, an event leading to days of bloody clashes killing 61
Palestinians and 15 Israelis. 
</P>
