<HEADLINE> Production, Sales and Use of Mines Banned in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, February 26 (Xinhua) -- The Ministers of Council today
endorsed a resolution which decides to ban the production, sales,
use and transport without permission of anti-personnel mines.
</P>
<P>
A news release issued here said the Mozambican government "has
decided as from now to ban the production, sales, use and
transport without permission of anti-personnel mines on its
territory."
</P>
<P>
The decision was taken when the the Fourth International
Conference against Mines is being held here.
</P>
<P>
The release said, "the Mozambican government indicates its
wishes to see the world refrain from the dangers of
anti-personnel mines and considers it imperative to remove and
destroy the mines which are posing danger to the people."
</P>
<P>
Maputo appeals to the international community to provide
assistance to countries like Mozambique, helping them rid of the
mines planted on their territories.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that between 1.5 and 3 million mines are now
left on the land of Mozambique during the past decades of civil
war.
</P>
<P>
Over 400 delegates from 60 countries are attending the
three-day conference sponsored by non-governmental organizations
aimed at seeking to ban the production and sales of mines.
</P>
