<HEADLINE> Nigeria Denies Responsibility for Canceled UN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 26 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government today
denied the alleged responsibility for the canceled visit by a
delegation of the United Nations Human Rights Commission.
</P>
<P>
"The government is satisfied that it had put in so much
toward the preparation for the joint mission and there is much
more to it than meetings with any particular individual to
warrant aborting or postponing it on account of lack of agreement
on such minor issues," said a government statement.
</P>
<P>
Param Comaraswany, the U.N. Special Rapporteur on the
Judiciary and Independence of Judges, and Bakre W. Ndiaye, his
counterpart on extra-judicial and summary executions, were
scheduled to begin a 10-day visit to Nigeria last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
But a row between them and the Nigerian government over the
mission's mandate and scope prevented their tour as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Tuesday, a U.N. official in Geneva, Issac Bruto,
blamed the deadlock on the Nigerian government, saying it ruled
out the possibility for the special Rapporteur to see political
detainees, including opposition leader Moshood Abiola and others.
</P>
<P>
However, Nigeria argued it had at all points bent down to meet
the demands of the delegation which kept on putting obstacles
along the way.
</P>
<P>
Western countries have been attacking Nigeria on its human
rights situation. It reached its high tide when the Commonwealth
suspended Nigeria's membership following the government's
execution of Ken Saro-Wiwa and eight other minority activists in
1995. 
</P>
