<HEADLINE> French Information Pirate Costs Heavy Loss to FBI </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, February 26 (Xinhua) -- A 21-year-old computer genius
was condemned to 18 months in jail in suspense and 50,000 francs
(9,000 U.S. dollars) of fines by a Paris court Tuesday for
disguising as FBI Paris chief to get free telecommunication
services.
</P>
<P>
Anthony Chris Zboralski, who proved himself a computer genius
when he was nine years old, cost the U.S. intelligence service
250,000 U.S. dollars by presenting himself as the FBI Paris chief,
Thomas Baker, to use free teleconference services of the France
Telecom state telecommunication company.
</P>
<P>
Imitating the voice of Mr. Baker, Anthony talked on the phone
and on computer with his friends around the world -- all of them
veteran information pirates -- and build a global information
empire of his own.
</P>
<P>
Anthony now has signed a contract with book publisher Calmann
Levy to tell his adventure story -- under the form of a
"manifesto."
</P>
<P>
He said that he had set up a firm, Immunis, which was
specialized in providing advices to enterprises on how to fight
information piracy, and claimed that he was opposed to the
monopoly by France Telecom of France's information world.
</P>
<P>
Judge Francis Bruty of the 12th Correctional Chamber of the
Great Investigation Tribunal of Paris said that although he was
impressed by the story, Anthony must be punished for "abuse of
false quality and disguising of voice." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
